INSERT INTO `saal_artists_en` VALUES (2,'AILE ASSZONYI','<STRONG><BR><BR>[popimg]aile_asszonyi_3_1.jpg[/popimg]<BR><BR>AILE ASSZONYI</STRONG>, a soprano, has studied singing at the Estonian Academy of Music and learned further in Italy as well as the Netherlands. During recent years, Asszonyi has performed as a vocal soloist both in Estonia and her present homeland the Netherlands. In 2004, the singer was given a laureate title at the Queen Elisabeth`s Competition. In the same year there were also recitals in Belgium, Austria, and the debut in the United States at the Newport Music Festival.<BR><BR>In the concert repertoire of Aile Asszonyi there are soprano parts from Bach`s \"Matthaeus Passion\", Beethoven`s Symphony No. 9, Brahms`s \"German Requiem\", Orff`s \"Carmina Burana\", Faur√©`s \"Requiem\" and H√§ndel`s \"Messiah\". In addition there are opera roles: Despina (Mozart`s \"Cos√¨ fan tutte\"), Mimi (Puccini`s \"La Boheme\") and Adina (Donizetti`s \"The Love Potion\"). ',1);
INSERT INTO `saal_artists_en` VALUES (3,'ANNELY PEEBO','<BR><STRONG>[popimg]Anneli_Peebo.jpg[/popimg]</STRONG><BR><BR><EM>‚Äû‚Ä¶She has a voice with a beautiful timbre and the face of Madonna‚Ä¶\", \"Salzburger Nachrichten\" wrote after Annely Peebo`s performance in 2004 in Dvo&#345;ak`s Stabat Mater in Salzburg.</EM><BR><BR><STRONG>ANNELY PEEBO</STRONG> is highly valued in Europe as an opera singer as well as a solo performer. She has sung together with artists like Placido Domingo, Renato Bruson, Stefania Bonfadelli, and Andrea Bocelli and taken part in the opera projects of Strehleir, Arlaud and Fo.<BR><BR>After finishing piano studies and acquiring the diploma of conducting, Anneli Peebo, a mezzo-soprano, studied at the Viennese Music and Drama University in the solo singing and opera class of Professor Gerhard Kahry. In 1997, she became a resident member of the National Opera of Vienna, and at the same time her debut in the Vienna State Opera took place. Since then she has sung a great number of parts in different operas, and by now also the roles of Cenerentola, Rosina, Zaida, Dorabella, Donna Elvira, Cherubino, Sesto, Idamante, H√§nsel, Carmen, Octavian, Boccaccio, Henry, Niklaus, Medoro, Dido, Hermia, Marquise Melibea, Mercedes, Maddalena, Flora, Orlofsky, etc. belong to her voluminous repertoire. In 2003, Annely Peebo sang at the performance of Beethoven`s Symphony No. 9 in Vatican, which was dedicated to the 25th anniversary of the inauguration of Pope Johannes Paul II.<BR><BR>After her debut at the Opera Festival of Savonlinna in the role of Niklaus in Offenbach`s \"The Tales of Hoffmann\", she received several offers for performances, among those a solo night in Trieste, concerts in Gewandhaus in Leipzig and Florence, Rome and Helsinki. ',1);
INSERT INTO `saal_artists_en` VALUES (4,'JUHAN TRALLA','<BR><STRONG>[popimg]Tralla_Juhan.jpg[/popimg]</STRONG><BR><BR><STRONG>JUHAN TRALLA</STRONG> has graduated from the Tallinn Music School in 1993 and the Estonian Academy of Music in 1997 in the specialty of violin. At the same time he studied singing in the class of Professor Mati Palm. In 1998‚Äì2001 Tralla studied singing at the Vienna Music University in the class of Professor Gerhard Kahry. Since 2003, he studies in Vienna at the singing studio of Professor Toma Popescu.<BR><BR>In 2000‚Äì2003 Juhan Tralla worked as a soloist in the Volksoper Wien during the seasons of 2003/2004, and in 2004/2005 he sang in the German National Theatre in Weimar. Since the autumn of 2005, Juhan Tralla is a freelance singer.<BR><BR>Among his most significant roles Juhan Tralla mentions the following: Tamino, Belmonte, don Ottavio, Idomeneo, and Titus (Mozart`s \"The Magic Flute\", \"The Abduction from the Seraglio\", \"Don Giovanni\", \"Idomeneo\", \"La Clemenza di Tito\"), Rodolfo, Rinuccio (Puccini`s \"La Boheme\", \"Gianni Schicchi\"), Almaviva, Othello (Rossini`s \"The Barber of Sevilla\", \"Othello\") Alfred (J. Strauss`s \"The Bat\"), Wheelman (Wagner`s \"The Flying Dutchman\"), etc.<BR><BR>In the National Opera Estonia Juhan Tralla has repeatedly sung the part of Alfredo (Verdi`s \"Traviata\"). As a soloist of great works he has performed as a tenor in Bach`s Mass in H-minor, Beethoven`s Symphony No. 9, masses by Mozart, Dvo&#345;ak, Rossini and Puccini, Verdi`s \"Requiem\", etc.&nbsp; Juhan Tralla has won the Grand Prix at the Tiit Kuusik Song Contest (1997) and at the Sabin Dragoi Contest in Timisoara, Romania (2003). He has also performed in Israel, Iran, Russia, Latvia, Finland, etc. ',1);
INSERT INTO `saal_artists_en` VALUES (5,'FINE 5 DANCE THEATRE ','\r\n<br>[popimg]Teine_Tants_-_FINE_5.jpg[/popimg]<br><br>FINE 5 DANCE THEATRE is the second Estonian modern dance company after the Nordstar Dance Theatre. It started out as a collaboration of 5 dancers from the Nordstar Dance Theatre in 1992.   Fine 5 Dance Theatre has worked with choreographers representing different styles: Ren√© N√µmmik, Daniel Tinazzi, Eileen Jones, Cloude-Yane Roulin, Tommi Kitti etc.<br>From 1997 two dance artists - Tiina Ollesk and Ren√© N√µmmik, have led Fine 5 Dance Theatre. They are trying to find their own way of thinking in movements and combining different possibilities for improvisation and dance techniques.  Fine 5 has performed in USA, Sweden, Finland, Poland, Russia and Baltic States and has won prizes at Vitebsk Modern Dance Festival (Byelorussia) in 1992, 1993, 1995, 1999, 2001 and at Pinerolo Contemporary Dance Contest (Italy) in 1997.<br><br>T. Ollesk and R. N√µmmik have also established their own dance school. Fine 5 Dance School started as a centre for contemporary dance in 1994. Most of Estonian dance artists who are active now in contemporary dance have learned there. The school has hosted teachers from Finland, Sweden, England, France, Switzerland, Belgium, USA teaching modern dance, contemporary dance, and improvisation. Fine 5 students have performed around Estonia, in Lithuania and Poland. They have continued studies at dance universities in Estonia and Europe.\r\n',1);
INSERT INTO `saal_artists_en` VALUES (17,'ERI KLAS','<BR><STRONG>[popimg]Eri_Klas_07.jpg[/popimg]</STRONG><BR><BR>More than three decades of active conducting have earned <STRONG>Eri Klas</STRONG> the reputation of an internationally highly acclaimed and well-respected musician. In 1965, Eri Klas begun his career as conductor at the Estonian National Opera. Until today he has appeared with more than 100 symphony orchestras in 40 countries all over the world. At the moment Eri Klas is the principal conductor of The Moscow Novaya Opera. Since 2002, Mr. Klas has been the artistic director of the Tallinn Philharmonic Society. ',1);
INSERT INTO `saal_artists_en` VALUES (18,'ESTONIAN NATIONAL SYMPHONY ORCHESTRA','<BR><STRONG>ESTONIAN NATIONAL SYMPHONY ORCHESTRA</STRONG> is considered to have been founded in 1926. ERSO, which grew from a small radio orchestra to Estonia\' leading orchestra, presents music from Baroque works to the premieres of modern compositions. ERSO chief conductors have included Olav Roots, Roman Matsov, Neeme J√§rvi, Peeter Lilje, Leo Kr√§mer and Arvo Volmer. Since the fall of 2001, the orchestra\'s chief conductor and artistic director is Nikolay Alekseyev from St. Petersburg and since the 2002/2003 season, the orchestra\'s artistic advisor has been Paavo J√§rvi.<BR><BR>ERSO is made up of 100 musicians and the orchestra gives an average of 60 concerts during one season. is considered to have been founded in 1926. ERSO, which grew from a small radio orchestra to Estonia\' leading orchestra, presents music from Baroque works to the premieres of modern compositions. ERSO chief conductors have included Olav Roots, Roman Matsov, Neeme J√§rvi, Peeter Lilje, Leo Kr√§mer and Arvo Volmer. Since the fall of 2001, the orchestra\'s chief conductor and artistic director is Nikolay Alekseyev from St. Petersburg and since the 2002/2003 season, the orchestra\'s artistic advisor has been Paavo J√§rvi. ERSO is made up of 100 musicians and the orchestra gives an average of 60 concerts during one season. ',1);
INSERT INTO `saal_artists_en` VALUES (6,'THE NOVAYA OPERA THEATRE OF MOSCOW','<BR><A href=\"http://www.novayaopera.ru\">THE NOVAYA OPERA THEATRE OF MOSCOW</A> was founded in 1991 on the initiative of Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov and Evgeny Kolobov, Artistic Director of the theatre. Since its inception, the theatre, operating on the contemporary contract basis, has been a leading opera house in Russia, winning recognition from opera lovers and the most exacting critics. The artistic creed of the theatre can be defined as enthusiastic creative quest and bold innovation. <A href=\"http://novayaopera.ru/newsite/en/content/kolobov.html\">Evgeny Kolobov</A>, Artistic Director and Chief Conductor of the Novaya Opera, regards any score, whether classical or modern, as \"a springboard for interpretation\". Such productions as O Mozart! Mozart... based on the opera Mozart and Salieri by Rimsky-Korsakov and Mozart\'s Requiem, Rubinstein\'s The Demon, the musical performances Bravissimo, Rossini, Maria Callas, Viva Verdi! and musical divertisment Bellini. The Novaya Opera Theatre of Moscow has done some premiers in Russia with performances like Donizetti\'s Maria Stuart and Mussorgski\'s Boriss Godunov in first redaction of author. One of the theatre\'s most important principles is to ensure that the professional skills and versatility of the choir, the orchestra and the soloists are maintained at as high a level as possible. There are more then 70 operas and major vocal-symphonic compositions in the repertoire of the theatre.<BR><BR><A href=\"http://www.novayaopera.ru/content.php?page=orchestra\"></A><STRONG>THE NOVAYA OPERA ORCHESTRA</STRONG>, a versatile team of 110 brilliant musicians, is a full-fledged participant in the theatre\'s operatic performances. The important part assigned to the Orchestra has to do with the wide-ranging artistic interests of Evgeny Kolobov and the other conductors of the theatre - Evgeny Samoilov, Anatoly Gus, Sergei Lysenko, Dmitry Volosnikov and starting from the summer 2006 ‚Äì Eri Klas. In addition to playing for the Novaya Opera, the Orchestra appears frequently on the concert platform, performing symphony programs in the best concert halls of Russia, such as the Grand Hall of the Moscow Conservatory, the Tchaikovsky Concert Hall, the St. Petersburg Philharmonic, to mention a few. Its symphony repertoire is large and diversified, comprising symphonies and symphonic compositions. The Orchestra often performs concert programs with the Novaya Opera\'s soloists, choir and guest musicians and touring with the Imperial Russian Ballet. &nbsp; ',1);
