INSERT INTO `saal_artists_en` VALUES (22,'OLIVER KUUSIK','<BR><STRONG>[popimg]Oliver_Kuusik_vaike.JPG[/popimg]</STRONG><BR><BR><STRONG>OLIVER KUUSIK</STRONG> (1980) studied at the Estonian Academy of Music and Theatre (in the singing class of Pille Lill and Vergilius Noreika) and in 2006 finished his master\'s studies and graduated from the Opera Studio Guildhall School of Music and Drama in London under the direction of Rudolf Piernay. Most important roles included in his repertoire are: Don Ramiro (Rossini\'s \"La Cenerentola\"), Fenton (Verdi\'s \"Falstaff\"), Rinuccio (Puccini\'s \"Gianni Schicci\"), Don Ottavio (Mozart\'s \"Don Giovanni\", in Manchester and London), Polidoro (Mozart\'s \"La finta semplice\"), Peppe (Leoncavallo\'s&nbsp; \"I pagliacci\"), Der Weise (Hindemith\'s \"Hin und zur√ºck\"), Torquemada (Ravel\'s \"L\'heure espagnole\"), Edwin (Gilbert\'s and Sullivan\'s \"Trial by Jury\" at the International Gilbert and Sullivan Festival, UK), Brighella (Jonathan Dove\'s \"Little Green Swallow\"&nbsp; premiere in UK), Villager (≈ ostakovit≈°/ Fleishmani \"Rotchild\'s violin\" (with Liverpool Royal Symphony Orchestra). As the musical singer Enjolras (Claude-Michel Sch√∂nbergs ¬´&nbsp;Les Miserables&nbsp;¬ª, Cameron Macintosh Production), etc.<BR>As an appreciated chamber and oratorio soloist he has already participated in the performance of nearly twenty several large compositions (incl. H√§ndel\'s&nbsp; \"Messiah\", Haydn\'s \"The Creation\", Mozart\'s \"Requiem\", etc.) and has given concerts in Estonia, Latvia, Finland, Sweden, Norway, Russia, Germany, France and England. &nbsp; ',1);
INSERT INTO `saal_artists_en` VALUES (23,'HELI VESKUS','<BR><STRONG>HELI VESKUS</STRONG> graduated from the Estonian Academy of Music in 1997 having studied under L. Dombrovska-Keis. Studied at the Sibelius Academy in the class of A. V√§lkki-Aro. In 1998, finalist at \"Con Brio\" Festival. Made her debut as Donna Elvira (Mozart\'s \"Don Giovanni) at the Estonian National Opera in 1999. Since 2001, a soloist at the Estonian National Opera. Roles: Fiordiligi (Mozart\'s \"Cosi fan tutte\"), Annina (J. Strauss\'s \"A Night in Venice\"), Tatjana (Tchaikovsky\'s \"Eugene Onegin\"), Mimi (Puccini\'s \"La Boh√®me\"), Kseniya (Mussorgski\'s \"Boriss Godunov\"), Wise Woman (Orff\'s \"The Wise Woman\"), Hanna Glawari (Leh√°r\'s \"Die lustige Witwe\"), Miss Pinkerton (Menotti\'s \"The Old Maid and the Thief\"), Agatha (Weber\'s \"Der Freisch√ºtz\"), Julia (K√ºnneke\'s \"The Cousin from Nowhere\"), Franziska Cagliari and Countess Gabriele Zedlau (Strauss\'s \"Wiener Blut\"), Liisu (Steiner\'s \"Wooing\"), Mica√´la (Bizet\'s \"Carmen\"), High Priestess (Verdi\'s \"Aida\"), Barbara (Tubin\'s \"Barbara von Tisenhusen\"), Mother (Kaumann\'s \"Me ‚Äì Napoleon!\"), Desdemona (Verdi\'s \"Othello\"), Floria Tosca (Puccini\'s \"Tosca\"), Nedda (Leoncavallo \"I pagliacci\"), etc.<BR>In summer 2006, she sung at the Opera Cava Festival the role of Agatha in Weber\'s opera \"Der Freisch√ºtz\". She has participated in the performance of several large compositions: Mozart\'s \"Requiem\", Great Mass in C minor and \"Coronation Mass\", Beethoven\'s Mass in C Major, Bruch \"Moses\", etc. She has given many solo concerts with pianist Jaanika Rand-Sirp. &nbsp; ',1);
INSERT INTO `saal_artists_en` VALUES (24,'Andjey Beletsky','<BR><STRONG>Andjey Beletsky</STRONG> (baritone) graduated from the Tula State Musical College (piano class) and the Russian Academy of Theatre Arts (Music Theatre Artist class).<BR>In 1994, Andjey Beletsky, still a student, joined the Helicon Opera Theatre of Moscow, where he has performed major baritone parts. From 1992 to 1996, he also was a soloist with the Moscow Kremlin Choir under G. Dmitryak. &nbsp; Andjey Beletsky joined the Novaya Opera Theatre of Moscow in 2001 and has performed the following parts: Demon in the cognominal opera by Rubinstein, Talbot in Maria Stuarda by Donizetti, Germont in La Traviata and Nabucco in Nabucco by Verdi, Orator in Die Zauberfl√∂te by Mozart. <BR>Andjey Beletsky has often performed in concert halls, in his repertoire there are opera arias and romances by Russian and foreign composers. Andjey Beletsky is a Companion of the Order ‚ÄûFor the Renaissance of Russia. XXI century\" and an awardee of the International Competition ‚ÄûPilar ‚Äì 2007\". ',1);
INSERT INTO `saal_artists_en` VALUES (25,'Galina Badikovskaya ','<BR><STRONG>Galina Badikovskaya</STRONG> (soprano) graduated from the Moscow State Conservatory in 1998. In 1997, Galina made her debut at the Novaya Opera Theatre of Moscow. <BR>At the Novaya Opera Galina Badikovskaya has performed as Tatyana in Tchaikovsky\'s Eugene Onegin, Tamara in Rubinstein\'s The Demon, Kupava in Rimsky-Korsakov\'s The Snow Maiden, Santuzza in Mascagni\'s Cavalleria Rusticana. &nbsp; The singer took part in the joint CD recording of the Novaya Opera Theatre of Moscow and the Choir of Savonlinna Opera Festival (Finland), where she performed the part of Santuzza in Cavalleria Rusticana. She also participated in the production of Tchaikovsky\'s Eugene Onegin in France and Germany.<BR style=\"mso-special-character: line-break\"><BR style=\"mso-special-character: line-break\">Galina Badikovskaya is a laureate of the Second All-Russia Competition for Young Performers. &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; ',1);
INSERT INTO `saal_artists_en` VALUES (26,'Elvira Khokhlova ','<BR><STRONG>Elvira Khokhlova</STRONG> (soprano) graduated from the Gnessins Russian Academy of Music. She joined the Novaya Opera Theatre in 1994 being a junior student. Her debute was Lucrezia in Verdi\'s I Due Foscari. She has performed parts of: Lyudmila in Glinka\'s Ruslan and Lyudmila,&nbsp; Xenia in Mussorgsky\'s Boris Godunov, Tamara in Rubinstein\'s The Demon, Nedda in Leoncavallo\'s I Pagliacci, etc. &nbsp; Elvira Khokhlova has also taken part in the theatre\'s concerts, performing arias from the classical opera repertoire, romances by Russian and foreign composers.<BR>&nbsp;<BR>The singer tours extensively with the Novaya Opera company in Russia and other countries. She participated in many opera productions abroad, such as Iolanta (the Monte Carlo Theatre, 2001), Norma, Pagliacci, Lucia di Lammermoor (Germany, Ulm and D√ºsseldorf, 2003-2006), Rigoletto (the 2nd Opera Festival in La Palma, Spain, 2005), and others. ',1);
