INSERT INTO `saal_events_en` VALUES (154,'','<p>ON TOUR:</p>\r\n<p>29+31.01&nbsp;&nbsp;Austrian Dance Platform, Graz /AUS/<br /><a href=\"http://www.impulstanz.com/news/headlines/548/en\">http://www.impulstanz.com/news/headlines/548/en</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&acute;They say folks who can manage big things never can manage little ones.&acute;</p>\r\n<p>A proper fairy tale told by a narrating princess. A handheld dinosaur speaks prophetic wisdom. A mesmerizing adventure video uncovers ancient truths. Of all performances possible, this is one of them.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Kr&otilde;&otilde;t Juurak was born in Tallinn. She has studied choreography at the Arnhem Institute of the Arts and visual arts at the Gerrit Rietveld Academie Amsterdam. Her works, often conceptual and ironic, have been performed at various dance festivals in Estonia, Austria, Germany, Switzerland, Moldova, Ukraine etc. Presently working and living between Tallinn and Vienna.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>idea: Kr&otilde;&otilde;t Juurak<br />performance: Kr&otilde;&otilde;t Juurak<br />dramaturgy: Berno Odo Polzer<br />co-produced by: Kanuti Gildi SAAL, dietheater Wien<br />supported by: Kulturabteilung der Stadt Wien<br />duration: 45&acute;</p>\r\n<p>premiere: 12.10.2006</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',1,'','<p class=\"suur\">KR&Otilde;&Otilde;T JUURAK</p>\r\n<p class=\"keskmine\">\"Once Upon\"</p>');
INSERT INTO `saal_events_en` VALUES (155,'','<p>ON TOUR:</p>\r\n<p>04.02 Lissabon /PRT/<br />12.02 DOCK 11, Berliin /GER/<br />29.03 FERME DU BUISSON, Pariis /FRA/<br />24+25.04 Eisfabrik, Hannover /GER/<br />http://www.commedia-futura.de/index.php?option=com_content&amp;task=view&amp;id=24&amp;Itemid=51<br />05.05 new baltic dance festival, arts printing house, Vilnius /LTH/<br />http://www.dance.lt/new-baltic-dance<br />7+8.05 tanz nrw 09, tanzhaus nrw, D&uuml;sseldorf /GER/<br />http://www.tanzhaus-nrw.de/de/spielplan/?month=05</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>In her interdisciplinary dance performance, Cologne-based choreographer Silke Z. explores the idea of the private sphere. Her work is a convergence of live performance, video installation and narrative film. A male and female dancer create an emotional landscape shaped by the dynamic interplay between closeness and distance, control and powerlessness. Private spheres emerge from which the audience cannot escape - they move throughout an installation that surrounds the performance on all four sides. The traditional stage is replaced by a space in which everyone shares in a common experience.<br />\"private spaces (the p.s. project)\" was created during residencies spent in Tallinn, Newcastle and D&uuml;sseldorf. In her choreography work, Silke Z. intensively examines interpersonal relationships and encounters between performers and audiences. In her last project, \"machMut\", from the 2007 series Mutproben, the performers she worked with included young adults. \"machtMut\" received the 2008 K&ouml;lner Tanz und Theaterpreis (Cologne Dance and Theatre Prize) and was nominated for the 2008 German theatre award DER FAUST. \"private spaces (the p.s. project)\" received also the K&ouml;lner Tanz und Theaterpreis 2008 (Cologne Dance and Theatre Prize)</p>\r\n<p>The line between discomfort and pain has long been crossed as the incredible performer Antonio Cabrita repeatedly hurls himself onto the floor in an attempt to finally illicit a reaction from his self-composed Caroline Simon with his self destruction. For the audience, there is nothing in space separating them from the performers; they are together in the same black enclosure. There is no longer an external world, only mercilessly exposed inner worlds. They want to run. They want to stay.<br />The audience personally experiences the dualism of society\'s need for discretion and curiosity about other people\'s private spheres. At what point is our search for authenticity shameful, when is it truly courageous?<br />In her outstanding production, Silke Z. probes the terror and beauty of intimacy. She has once again succeeded in succinctly capturing a current and indeterminate phenomenon that defies general explanation.<br />Reality, for Silke Z., is bouquet of splinters. Beautiful to behold - but with dangerously sharp edges. <br />Nicole Strecker, K&ouml;lner Tanzpreis award speech</p>\r\n<p>Silke Z. born in 1970, lives and works as an independent choreographer in Cologne. She studied dance and skiing at the Deutsche Sporthochschule K&ouml;ln, completed training at the European Dance Development Center (EDDC) in Arnheim and D&uuml;sseldorf and pursued further training at San Francisco&acute;s Moving On Center - School for Participatory Arts and Research.<br />Silke Z. is a co-founder of resistdance, Studio 11, and die.idee//artist network.<br />Her production, \"fractured\" was honoured with the cologne dance award in 1999 and the F&ouml;rderpreis freier Theater NRW Theaterzwang. Her production \"CAUGHT UP\" was developed at CHOREODROME at THE PLACE/LONDON and selected for the dance award Cologne 2003.<br />Her production \"Look\" was honoured with the dance award of the festival Theaterzang 2004. Her production \"Alife\" 2004 was selected for dance award Cologne 2004. <br />Her works have been presented at the Aerowaves Festival in London, at the Baltic Dance Festival in Vilnius/Lithuania and by Dance Link in Den Haag/the Netherlands. <br />Since 2005 she has worked on a series called MUTPROBEN/DARE PROJECT that she has been developing in coproduction with the Orangerie in Cologne, Eisfabrik Hannover and the Ludwigforum in Aachen. In 2006 that series continued at Tanzhaus NRW and at Counterpulse Theater in San Francisco. All Mutproben/DARE Projects are full evening pieces containing dance, theatre, video, live-sound design and other related performance arts. A compilation of all Mutproben/DARE PROJECTS (1-5) in September 2006 lead to the production called \":&uuml;berMut\" at the tanzhaus nrw and was then touring in various cities in Germany such as Aachen, K&ouml;ln, Hannover etc.<br />2007 she produced in the course of \"take off\", Tanzplan Deutschland the production \"machtMut\" at the tanzhaus nrw. A production which combines professional dancers and adolescents on one stage.<br />From 2004 until 2008 she was the artistic director for the dance series TANZKONKRET in Cologne, a platform for local and national dance work.<br />Since 2007 Silke Z. very often works with foreign partners. \":&uuml;berMut\" was part of the Festival Jonge Harten/Groningen in November 2007.<br />\"machtMut\" was granted with the Cologne Dance and Theatre Award 2008 and was nominee for DER FAUST, the German theatre award 2008.<br />private spaces was selected for favoriten08/Theaterzwang , a regional festival for theatre and dance and was also granted with the Cologne Dance and Theatre Award 2008</p>\r\n<p>Caroline Simon was born in Brussels in 1977. She studied contemporary dance at the Performing Arts Research and Training Studios, directed by AnneTeresa de Keersmaeker. She graduated in June 2001 at the Rotterdam Dance Academy as a dancer, dance teacher and choreographer.<br />She performed in performances by Minke Brands (NL), Ex Nihilo (F), Ilona P&aacute;szthy, Katja F. M. Wolf, Alexandra Dederichs and Silke Z. (D). Since May 2001, Caroline Simon lives and works in Cologne, where she produces her own work: \"Time Trap - or short genuine stories\" (2002), \"descent\" (2003) and \"BLUFF\" (2004), nominated for the Cologne Dance Award 2004, \"Bluff II and Flooded\" (2005), \"SELECT!\" (2006).<br />Since April 2005 she is the artistic director of STUDIO 11, a production studio in Cologne for free lance theatre and dance makers. In 2006 she received the choreography grant from the Kunststiftung NRW for somatic studies in San Francisco.<br />In 2008, together with the companies Lupita Pulpo (Berlin), Ludica. (D&uuml;sseldorf) and silke.z:resistdance. (Cologne), she co-founded of the nationwide network die.idee // bewegt sich // artist network. Her solo \"piece\" was nominated for the Cologne dance and theatre award 2008 and has been selected for the European festival Aerowaves!</p>\r\n<p>Antonio Cabrita studied in Lisbon at the National Conservatoire\'s Dance School and at the Restart School of Creativity and New Technologies. In New York he also studied at the Joffrey Ballet School and at the New York Film Academy, and worked, as well, in his first independent project, while made his first short-film - \"Ma&ccedil;&atilde;\". Back in Portugal, he collaborated with independent projects, did exhibitions as a photographer and composed the original score for three plays and two movies. As a film-maker he directed several short films and dance films</p>\r\n<p><br />--------------------------------------------------------------------------------</p>\r\n<p>Concept &amp; choreography: Silke Z.<br />Dance &amp; performance: Caroline Simon, Antonio Cabrita<br />Concept, filmdirecting: Andr&eacute; Zimmermann<br />Dramaturgy: Silke Z., Andr&eacute; Zimmermann<br />Technical director: Ansgar Kluge<br />Film/video design: Jan Hanten, Andr&eacute; Zimmermann<br />Light and stage design: Ansgar Kluge<br />Sound design: Christian Azadi<br />Supervision: Rudi Kamminga (Grand Theatre Gronningen, Holland)<br />Production management: Katja Steinbach<br />Production assistance: Irena Vujicic<br />Management/pr: Mechtild Tellmann<br />Photos: Jan Hanten, Hydra Productions<br />Co-produced by: Kanuti Gildi SAAL (Tallinn), DanceCity (Newcastle) and tanzhaus nrw (D&uuml;sseldorf)<br />Supported by: Kulturamt der Stadt K&ouml;ln, Kunststiftung NRW, Ministerpr&auml;sident des Landes NRW, SK Stiftung Kultur<br />Production: silke z. / resistdance</p>\r\n<p>Performances in Tallinn are supported by: Goethe Institut Tallinn, City of K&ouml;ln</p>\r\n<p>http://www.resistdance.com/</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',1,'','<p class=\"suur\">SILKE Z / resistdance &amp; friends</p>\r\n<p class=\"keskmine\">\"private spaces (the p.s. project)</p>');
INSERT INTO `saal_events_en` VALUES (156,'','<p>ON TOUR:</p>\r\n<p>5+6.06&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Espa&ccedil;o do Tempo, Montemor-O-Novo, Montemor /POR/<br />26.11&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;SAAL[&auml;tt]Tartu, Genialistide klubi, Tartu</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>In her physical theatre/contemporary dance performance the up-and-coming Estonian choreographer Sandra Z will try to capture the dynamics of a concert of a musical masterpiece, like ... Vivaldi \"The Four Seasons\". After a concert you never ask what it was about or why one harmony followed another the way it did. No social or political plot, all the visual effects are strictly personal and indescribable in any other way. It\'s time. It\'s time to notice. It\'s time to notice others.\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Sandra Z is a freelance choreographer and performer. She studied dance at Fine 5 Dance School in Tallinn and Dartington College of Arts in London. Lead vocal in Estonian death metal band Deceased Dreams and disco pop project QueeN-Naive. In 2006, she won the concourse &bdquo;Best project for young choreographer\" by Estonian Cultural Endowment, with project for &bdquo;The Bekinning\". She has participated in workshops with Thomas Lehmen, Didier Deschamps, Caroline Waters. She has worked also with Stefan Kaegi (Rimini Protokoll) as actor/singer in Cargo Sofia in Tallinn (2008). In 2009 she was chosen to be part of the LOOPING project for young emerging choreographers and in June 2009 premiered her latest work &bdquo;It\'s Time\".</p>\r\n<p>Her current ambition is to enhance the dialogue between performers and critics and to update the directing techniques in both theatre and dance.</p>\r\n<p><br />--------------------------------------------------------------------------------</p>\r\n<p>Direction: Sandra Z<br />Choreography: Alissa &Scaron;naider, Sandra Z<br />Performance: Sandra Z<br />Music: Taavi Tulev / Wochtzchee<br />Scenography: Tuuli Antsov<br />Coproduced by: Kanuti Gildi SAAL, Espa&ccedil;o do Tempo at Montemor-O-Novo /PRT/<br />Performance is produced in cooperation with LOOPING network and with the support of EU Culture program.<br />Supported by: Cultural Endowment of Estonia</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://breakingitstime.blogspot.com/\">http://breakingitstime.blogspot.com/</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>[img] logo-looping-oh.jpg [/img]</p>\r\n</p>',1,'','<p class=\"suur\">SANDRA Z</p>\r\n<p class=\"keskmine\">\"It&acute;s Time!\"</p>');
INSERT INTO `saal_events_en` VALUES (157,'','<p>13+14.03&nbsp;&nbsp;Mix&acute;Art Myrys, Toulouse /FRA/<br /><a href=\"http://www.mixart-myrys.org/program/programation.htm\">http://www.mixart-myrys.org/program/programation.htm</a><br />6.04&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;INACHEVES, Theatre Saragosse, Pau /FRA/<br /><a href=\"http://www.espacespluriels.fr/rubrique.php3?id_rubrique=32\">http://www.espacespluriels.fr/rubrique.php3?id_rubrique=32</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Substantially &lsquo;Ball\' tries to broaden the relation inbetween a dance couple until its transformation to between the audience and the performer. What happens, if it would be the audience who is asked to &lsquo;the dance\' by the performer? Practically the performers are interested in how in the situation of performance is possible to stay true to yourself (for spectators as well), because when dancing together the lie has short legs and communication has to stay sincere, otherwise nothing will come out of this dance.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&lsquo;Ball\' is the first cooperation between two young choreographers and performers Nele Suisalu from Tallinn and Florent Hamon from Toulouse.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>idea, direction, choreography, performance: Nele Suisalu, Florent Hamon<br />sound and light design: Nicolas Gastard<br />photos: Benjamin Rupin<br />producer: Nomad\'act<br />co-production: Kanuti Gildi SAAL<br />supporters: Cultural Endowment of Estonia; Centre chor&eacute;graphique national de Montpellier Languedoc-Roussillon; Etre en sc&egrave;ne / Compagnie Yann Lheureux<br />Tallinn performance supporter: French Cultural Centre<br />duration: 65&acute;<br />premiere: 28.08.2008</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',1,'','<p><span class=\"suur\">NELE SUISALU &amp; FLORENT HAMON</span><br /><span class=\"keskmine\">\"Ball\"</span></p>');
INSERT INTO `saal_events_en` VALUES (158,'','<p><br />Already the earlier works of Renate Valme have pointed out her unique ability to present her personal poetic perception of the world by using convincing and individual visual language.<br />Previously she has been presenting her worlds together with the other artists. This time she is on the stage alone. Alone with things. And since things are pretty cold and single valued on their own then she is looking for ways how to find shortcuts via things into a kind of second, more semantic, beautiful and happy world.<br />How to reach the easiness of a playing child. In order that the things were not merely what they are, but that the things could change meaning and purpose according to the will of the performer. So that the reality would not be so frigidly monosemantic.\r\n<p>&acute;Second Land&acute;premiered in August 2008 at the Homo Alibi festival in Riga, Latvia.</p>\r\n<p>Renate Valme is a freelance choreographer. She gratuated as a choreographer from Tartu University Viljandi Culture Academy. Her shows &acute;mobile home&acute;, &acute;MESTA&acute; and &acute;Idula&acute; have deserved recognition both in Estonia and on various festivals abroad. She has also worked as a choreography and actor on productions in several Estonian theatres.</p>\r\n<p>idea, direction, performance: Renate Valme<br />co-produced by: The New Theatre Institute of Latvia, Kanuti Gildi SAAL<br />supported by: Cultural Endowment of Estonia and Cultural Endowment of Latvia<br />duration: 50\'<br />ticket: 70/120.-<br />NB! Premiere in Latvia August 29 2008</p>\r\n</p>',1,'','<p class=\"suur\">RENATE VALME</p>\r\n<p class=\"keskmine\">\"Second Land\"</p>');
INSERT INTO `saal_events_en` VALUES (159,'','<p>23+24.04&nbsp;&nbsp;KokoTeatteri, Helsingi /FIN/&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<br /><a href=\"http://www.kokoteatteri.fi/\">http://www.kokoteatteri.fi/</a><br />23.05 / 20:00&nbsp;&nbsp;MUUSIKA S6PRADELE, Genialistide Klubi, Tartu&nbsp;<br />24.05 / 21:00&nbsp;&nbsp;Genialistide Klubi, Tartu&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<br />30.07 / 19:00&nbsp;&nbsp;Sulattofestivaali, Karkkila /FIN/&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<br />18.09&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Tehdasfestivaali Manifesti, Turku /FIN/</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The dancer Kaja Kann and the sound artist Juha Valkeap&auml;&auml; have been creating songs since childhood. The show they are doing in Kanuti Gildi SAAL has been shown at different Lokaals in Europe and all over the world. The group comes together every once in a while. The audience will certainly hear their infamous piece \"Money\" and other well-known and much heard songs.</p>\r\n<p>The repertoire of the duet Kann/Valkep&auml;&auml; consists of very varied pieces. They have been inspired by the old rock legend Mark Lanegan as well as Ali Farka Toure. 2 guitars and an overwhelming voice that will however leave space for physical movement. It will most certainly not leave the audience tepid as the Kann/Valkeap&auml;&auml; duet has received both very positive and very negative responses, they have been loved and hated. It is obvious that the band enjoys their performance sharing this delight with the audience even though their songs lack classic structure and easily recognizable reprises.</p>\r\n<p>Kaja Kann (1973) is known for her unconventional mastery of vocal and guitar techniques. One thing is certain - she enjoys movement and smoky clubs. Kaja Kann has messed around on stage on many more occasions than she would like remembering. And she keeps doing it again and again. Kaja sais that it is enjoyable to wander alone and then discover that she is with Juha and it is especially terrific if the audience is present as well. This is not witty choreography, this is dance.</p>\r\n<p>Already in his early years Juha Valkeap&auml;&auml; (1967) made bizarre sounds to express himself. In his teens he discovered the electric guitar following the pattern of Jimmy Hendrix. Besides this duet he has been part of several folk, punk-rock, alternative sound space and improvisational projects. He likes to take risks. Sometimes it seems like he can understand his partner even without words, without composing. If this takes place on stage then it feels peculiar.</p>\r\n<p><br />--------------------------------------------------------------------------------</p>\r\n<p>Idea, performance: Kaja Kann, Juha Valkeap&auml;&auml; <br />Original music: Juha Valkeap&auml;&auml;<br />Choreography: Kaja Kann<br />Design: Maike Lond<br />Photo: Evert Palmets<br />Technical realisation: Kalle Tikas<br />Co-produced by: Kanuti Gildi SAAL, Eksperimentaalse Liikumise Keskus<br />Supporters: Cultural Endowment of Estonia, Estonian National Culture Foundation, Cultural Heritage Department of Tallinn City Council, Embassy of Finland in Tallinn, Finnish Institute in Tallinn, Finnish Cultural Foundation, Arts Council of Finland<br />Premiere: 19.03.2009 bar-club Juuksur / Hairdresser</p>\r\n<p><br />Listen to them also at: http://www.myspace.com/kannvalkeapaa</p>\r\n<p>www.tants.ee/trupid/eesti/zuga/#kaja<br />http://www.nbl.fi/~nbl815/</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',1,'','<p><span class=\"suur\">KAJA KANN &amp; JUHA VALKEAP&Auml;&Auml;</span> /FIN/<br /><span class=\"keskmine\">\"At Lokaal tonight: Kann/Valkeap&auml;&auml;\" </span></p>');
INSERT INTO `saal_events_en` VALUES (160,'','<p>An effortless<br />Springly molecule<br />Alt Nurmekurg<br />Kolkhosnik by maiden name\r\n<p>Or have my dreams<br />Been too short for too long a time?<br />Alt Nurmekurg<br />Wife of a fisherman</p>\r\n<p>Maybe not quite petit-bourgeois<br />But still pretty extra-terrestrial <br />Alt Nurmekurg<br />The Raven with Silver Wings</p>\r\n<p>Triin Reemann is one of the most outstanding young choreographers in Estonia who made reknown for herself already with her diploma work at the Tartu University Viljandi Culture Academy where she studied choreography. Her production \"Hea Kuudis\" was well received both in Estonia and elsewhere. She herself calls her dancing style \"printing choreographics\".</p>\r\n<p><br />--------------------------------------------------------------------------------</p>\r\n<p>Idea, direction: Triin Reemann<br />Performance: K&auml;rt Reemann, Silver Elvest<br />Designer: Epp Kubu<br />Composer, musician: Silver Sepp <br />Technical solution: Revo Koplus<br />Co-produced by: Kanuti Gildi SAAL<br />Supporter: Cultural Endowment of Estonia<br />Premiere: 04.03.2009 Kanuti Gildi SAAL<br />Meet the artists: 05.03 after the performance. Moderator: Laur Kaunissaare (in Estonian).</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>[popimg] reemann-02.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] reemann-03.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg]</p>\r\n</p>',1,'','<p class=\"suur\">TRIIN REEMANN</p>\r\n<p class=\"keskmine\">\"Kalamees ja kurg\"</p>');
INSERT INTO `saal_events_en` VALUES (161,'','<p>9+10+11+12.05 Kunstenfestivaldesarts Brussels, Br&uuml;ssel /BEL/ <br />10.07 / 20:00 NoTaFe, vana spordihoone, Viljandi <br />19+20.08 far&deg; - festival des arts vivants, Nyon /SUI/ <br />09.09 Homo Novus festival, Riia /LAT/ <br />18+19+20.09 De (Internationale) Keuze Dans Festival, Rotterdam /HOL/ <br />23+24.11 SAAL[&auml;tt]Tartu, Genialistide klubi, Tartu</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>After a pause one of the most internationally acclaimed contemporary Estonian choreographers, Mart Kangro is back again in SAAL with a new solo.</p>\r\n<p>The core of Mart Kangro\'s aesthetic language could probably be summed up as a tension between two sides. Everyday actions in close-up on the one hand. And a commentary on commonplace contemporary performance art forms laying bare the way these function and are perceived.</p>\r\n<p>All of this has an aim, a target. He makes use of his own and the audience\'s previous experience and prejudices in having seen grand shows and spectacles. Laying bare their structure and reflecting back the hopes of the audience Kangro leads the spectators into seeing his performance as what it is, not what it is not. For this he uses various types of stage games that lead the spectator into thinking about the paradoxes and forces around how a stage performance is perceived. What he does is a commentary on experience. He leads the audience into awareness of their own perception and finding their own unmediated approach to the work onstage. He makes the spectator realise his preconceptions and hopes, kind of left-over from previously viewed performances. Spectacular episodes exist in his shows but at places where one wouldn\'t expect them.</p>\r\n<p>In his new solo \"Can\'t Get No / Satisfaction\" Mart Kangro will try to investigate how it affects the performer to know that what he does depends directly on the reaction of the audience. That it is only through a certain agreement with the audience that the performer is on stage at all. What compromises are necessary on the part of the performer in order for his artistic idea to be received and to be able to satisfy the audience?</p>\r\n<p>The audience has the justified right to an emotional recharge. On the other hand, the artist has the right to be understood and give to the audience his artistic idea. A conflict? Possibly. Both sides collide and create a paradoxical situation.</p>\r\n<p>Possibly one of the most internationally acclaimed contemporary Estonian choreographers Mart Kangro focuses in his work on the meanings the body and movements create and the concept of meaning in theatre as a semiotic time-space. Kangro has been engaged as a dancer at the Estonian National Opera. As a choreographer he has for a long time collaborated with Christina Ciupke and Thomas Lehmen. He has created 8 full-length dance pieces that have been presented in more than 20 countries all over Europe and North America.</p>\r\n<p><br />--------------------------------------------------------------------------------</p>\r\n<p>Idea and performance: Mart Kangro<br />Music: Taavi Kerikm&auml;e<br />Dramaturgical assistance: Petra Roggel, Christina Ciupke<br />Technical solutions: Kalle Tikas<br />Co-produced by: Kanuti Gildi SAAL, Baltoscandal 2010 festival (Rakvere, Estonia), De Internationale Keuze van de Rotterdamse Schouwburg, Kunstenfestivaledesarts Brussels<br />Project co-produced by NXTSTP, with the support of the Culture Programme of the European Union<br />Supported by: Cultural Endowment of Estonia<br />Premiere: 21.01.09 Kanuti Gildi SAAL<br />NB! Performances on 22 and 23 of January are in English!<br />Meet the artists: 22.01 after the performance. Moderator: Laur Kaunissaare (in English).</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',1,'','<p><span class=\"suur\">MART KANGRO</span><br /><span class=\"keskmine\">\"Can&acute;t Get No / Satisfaction\"</span></p>');
INSERT INTO `saal_events_en` VALUES (162,'','<p><strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">TARMO TAGAMETS \"anonymous WOMAN\"</span></strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The piece \"anonymous WOMAN\" is based on the quote by Charles Bukowski:<br />\"Human relations are queer. Meaning, you live together with one person, you eat and sleep with her, talk to her and go to places with her here and there. And then it ends. For a while you are alone and then comes the next woman. And you eat and sleep with her and it all feels so normal, like you had been waiting foe her and she had been waiting for you. I never felt right alone. Actually sometimes it was great to be alone, but it never felt right.\"<br />(H. C. Bukowski \"Women\", 1978)</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>To repeat is to learn for certain.</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>Direction: <a href=\"http://www.vorulinnateater.com/index.php?id=10556\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>Tarmo Tagamets</strong></a><br />Play: <a href=\"http://www.vorulinnateater.com/index.php?id=10560\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>Eleri J&uuml;risaar</strong></a><strong>, </strong><a href=\"http://www.vorulinnateater.com/index.php?id=10592\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>Agu Trolla</strong></a>, <strong>Tarmo Tagamets</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">MARIANNE K&Uuml;TT \"anonymous MAN\"</span></strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>A town. A house. A restaurant. a room. Maybe several. A man. A woman. Maybe several. Fear that someone is watching them. Maybe several watchers? A wish, a desire, a dream. Fear to fulfil those.</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>Direction: <strong>Marianne K&uuml;tt<br /></strong>Play: <a href=\"http://www.vorulinnateater.com/index.php?id=10559\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>Maive K&auml;os</strong></a>, <strong>Helgur Rosental</strong> (as a guest, freelance actor), <strong>Marianne K&uuml;tt</strong> (as a guest, freelance actor)</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>Supported by: <strong>V&otilde;ru Town, Cultural Ministry of Estonia, Cultural Endowment of Estonia, V&otilde;rumaa Teataja, Kultuuri.net<br /></strong>Premiere: <strong>21.11.09 V&otilde;ru Kultuurimaja Kannel</strong><br /><a href=\"http://www.vorulinnateater.com\"></a></p>\r\n<p>Duration: 80&acute; (with intermission)</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.vorulinnateater.com\">www.vorulinnateater.com</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>[popimg] tagamets-aman-01.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] tagamets-aman-02.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] tagamets-aman-03.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] tagamets-aman-04.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] tagamets-aman-05.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] tagamets-aman-06.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg]</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>PRESS:<br /></strong><a href=\"http://www.vorumaateataja.ee/?a=uudised&amp;b=10063\" target=\"_blank\">Fragmentaarne naine, olematu mees</a> - Veiko M&auml;rka / V&otilde;rumaa Teataja 26.11.09</p>',1,'','<p>V&otilde;ru Town Theatre:<br /><span class=\"keskmine\"><span class=\"suur\">TARMO TAGAMETS / MARIANNE K&Uuml;TT</span><br />\"anonymous MAN/anonymous WOMAN\"</span></p>');
INSERT INTO `saal_events_en` VALUES (164,'','<p>\"Bodysnatchers\" takes the spectators into a parallel world with its surreal characters, scaffolding cage and fanciful story. Rules and etiquette there are a mixture of that what we know of combined with overturned reality to make one think about the patterns of behaviour and rules of society. Choreography is physical and uses acrobatic techniques. Stage will be filled with vast scaffolding cage offering the audience a choice of observing points broadening the notion of stage space.</p>\r\n<p><strong><br />Mihkel Ernits</strong> is a freelance choreographer and currently he is obtaining MA degree in choreographer - director studies at Tallinn University Institute of Fine Arts Department of Choreography. In 2008 he made it to the semi final of the international contemporary dance contest C.o.n.t. est 08.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>K&uuml;lli Roosna</strong> is a freelance dancer, who has studied choreography at Tallinn University and Rotterdam Dance Academy. She is working with various choreographers in Holland, Sweden, Norway and Estonia. She has worked with different artists, such as Dylan Newcomb, Kenneth Flak, Aida Redza, Amy Raymond, Ezequiel Sanucci, Rene N&otilde;mmik, Tiina Ollesk, J&uuml;ri Nael, Kaarel V&auml;li. As a choreographer she has created short works and assisted staging bigger projects - \"Silence\", \"My Sounds\", \"Igo\"; 2008 Music Award Gala- In April 2010 she will present her new short piece \"Keerisena Kulgemine\". K&uuml;lli teaches dance technique and improvisation as visiting lector at Tallinn University and Fine 5 Dance Theatre. <a href=\"http://kulliroosna.com/\" target=\"_blank\">http://kulliroosna.com/</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Laura Kvelstein</strong> is a freelance dancer. She is a member of Fine 5 Dance Theatre and during the last ten years she has participated in the projects of local and international choreographers in Estonia and Holland and USA. In 2006 she was awarded with the grant of Best Young Dancer at the I.D.A dance festival in Tartu.</p>\r\n<p><strong><br /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Rain Saukas</strong> started dancing at Fine 5 Dance School in 2003. After two ywars of studying he continued as a member of Fine 5 Dance Theatre and since then he has participated at performances \"Panus\", \"Carmina Burana\", \"Reekviem\", \"Faasid\" and several other smaller projects. He earns his daily salary at disain agency Taevas as graphic designer.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>J&ouml;rgen Kapp</strong> has been top ball-room dancer; he has reached 5th place at youth world championship. He has been doing it for 12 years, since 2005 he is also a coach and judge. Right now he is simultaneously studying at the Department of Choreography at Tallinn University.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Maarja M&otilde;tus</strong> is a freelance designer, who currently is finishing her product design studies at the Estonian Art Academy. Previously she has been involved with fashion and costume design. She participated successfully at the Supernova fashion design contest in 2006 and she has attended workshops in Israel and Italy. In 2009 she had vocational practice with Isao Hosoe in Milan. Her curiosity towards dance got her engaged with creating the environment for this performance.</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>Idea: <strong>Mihkel Ernits</strong><br />Direction: <strong>K&uuml;lli Roosna, Mihkel Ernits</strong><br />Perfromers/choreographers: <strong>Rain Saukas, Laura Kvelstein, J&ouml;rgen Kapp, K&uuml;lli Roosna</strong><strong></strong><br />Light design: <strong>Revo Koplus</strong></p>\r\n<p>Stage design: <strong>Maarja M&otilde;tus</strong></p>\r\n<p>Sound design: <strong>Shawn Pinchbeck</strong></p>\r\n<p>Music:<strong> SPK, The Fun Years, Murcof</strong></p>\r\n<p>Text: <strong>Henry Griin</strong></p>\r\n<p>Make-up: <strong>Kaia Pihlak</strong></p>\r\n<p>Photo: <strong>Martin Sookael</strong></p>\r\n<p>Photos from rehealsal: <strong>Timo Toots</strong></p>\r\n<p>Co-producer: <strong>Kanuti Gildi SAAL</strong><br />Supporters: <strong>Cultural Endowment of Estonia, Metal-Disain O&Uuml;, Telinek AS</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Martin Sookael vol 1:</p>\r\n<p>[popimg] mihkel-martin-0120.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] mihkel-martin-01.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] mihkel-martin-02.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] mihkel-martin-03.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] mihkel-martin-04.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg]</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Martin Sookael vol 2:</p>\r\n<p>[popimg] m-m-oh-17.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] m-m-oh-16.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] m-m-oh-1549.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] m-m-oh-14.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] m-m-oh-13.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg]</p>\r\n<p>[popimg] m-m-oh-12.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] m-m-oh-11.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] m-m-oh-10.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] m-m-oh-09.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] m-m-oh-08.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg]</p>\r\n<p>[popimg] m-m-oh-07.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] m-m-oh-06.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] m-m-oh-05.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] m-m-oh-04.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] m-m-oh-03.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg]</p>\r\n<p>[popimg] m-m-oh-02.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] m-m-oh-01.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg]</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Timo Toots:</p>\r\n<p>[popimg] ernits-toots-02.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] ernits-toots-03.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] ernits-toots-05.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] ernits-toots-06.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] ernits-toots-09.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg]</p>\r\n<p>[popimg] ernits-toots-10.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] ernits-toots-14.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] ernits-toots-17.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] ernits-toots-35.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] ernits-toots-3816.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg]</p>\r\n<p>[popimg] ernits-toots-52.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] ernits-toots-53.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] ernits-toots-54.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] ernits-toots-58.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] ernits-toots-60.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg]</p>',1,'','<p><span class=\"suur\">MIHKEL ERNITS</span> <span class=\"keskmine\">\"Bodysnachers\"</span></p>');
