INSERT INTO `saal_events_en` VALUES (231,'','<p>73 years old Grigori from small town Paide had been dancing with his wife Aime for decades. In December 2008 his wife died. When 40 days had passed since her death Grigori started building a doll. He built a full-size doll, dressed the doll with the clothes of his wife and went to dance. In May 2010 he met dance teacher &Uuml;lle Toming and the idea to create a dance-piece emerged.\r\n<hr />\r\nPerformers: <strong>Grigori &Scaron;vets, doll Alice, &Uuml;lle Toming, ensemble \"Pihlamari\"</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>[popimg] grigori-01-oh.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg]  grigori-02-oh.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] grigori-03-oh.jpg %%  Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] grigori-04-oh.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg]  [popimg] grigori-05-oh.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg]</p>',1,'','<p><span class=\"suur\">GRIGORI &Scaron;VETS, &Uuml;LLE TOMING, ENSEMBLE \"PIHLAMARI\"</span><span class=\"keskmine\"> &bdquo;SAIME KOKKU SOLENZARAS\"</span><br />dance piece with man, woman and doll</p>');
INSERT INTO `saal_events_en` VALUES (232,'','<p>The choreographer Hooman Sharifi, of Iranian descent, tells of a country in which time has no special meaning. This is a country which has not happened yet, but yet it seems that it has always already been there. A country which still has to come, however it has already come long time ago. Because time is in abundance in this country, living together is experienced as a plurality of possible ways how people are coming into being. Since one is always exposed to the plurality of possible actions, people can live together in constant disagreement, but nevertheless they could also allow a problem to exist for such a long time that the best solution will appear. In this country of endless possibilities, the encounters between its inhabitants take place because of their radical refusal of any change. The performance explores the embodied relations of this imaginative land with plenty of time and the ways how distribution of bodies refuse change to make life possible. With that possibilities are created for the audience to imagine what would be the country with the plentitude of time, where movement is not depending exclusively on change.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Hooman Sharifi\'s works are of tremendous physical power. As spontaneous as they sometimes appear to be, their intensity is the result of meticulous consideration and choreography, a movement between theatre, dance and visual art. For Sharifi, like hardly any other contemporary choreographer, the motto is \"art is politics\" - and politics, to him, means social perception and commitment not by means of superficial analysis or easy-to-read representation of supposedly political topics. Instead he goes deeper, searching for the emotions and structures behind group hierarchies, violence, power and abuse.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Born and raised in Iran, <strong>Hooman Sharifi</strong> is now a Norwegian Citizen. He arrived in Norway solitarily in 1989 at the age of 15. His experience in dance started with hip-hop and street-jazz. Later, at the age of 21, came the technical training of classical ballet and modern dance. In 1997 he was accepted to the 3-year course in choreography with the National College of Ballet and Dance in Oslo, from which he graduated in spring 2000. He has always had an interest in the \"cross-work\" of dance and theatre, and after graduating he has worked with dramatic as well as visual art. In 2000 he established Impure Company. The statement \"art equals politics\" where social awareness and commitment defines the word politics marks the outset for Impure Company and signifies what art is and should be. Hooman Sharifi has been successfully invited to theatres and festivals in Estonia for several years.</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Choreography, direction and light:<strong> Hooman Sharifi</strong><br />Made and performed by: <strong>Rikke Baewert, Matthew William Smith, Loan Ha, Martin Lervik, Peder Horgen</strong><br />Artistic collaborator: <strong>Bojana Kunst</strong><br />Text: <strong>Daniel Franco and Hooman Sharifi</strong><br />Music: <strong>coh</strong><br />Tailor: Dylvia R. Denais<br />Artistic coordinator: Valerie Lanciaux<br />Production coordinator: Ida Gudbrandsen<br />Impure company production in co-production with Steirischer Herbst Graz, Dansens Hus Oslo, Dance &amp; Theatre Festival G&ouml;teborg<br />Thanks to Marianne Van Kerkhoven, tanzlabor 21 Mousonturm Frankfurt, In Transit 09 Berlin, Art Stations Foundation Poznan and Asle L. Pettersen<br />Impure company is supported by the Norwegian Council for Cultural Affairs, The Ministry of Foreign Affairs.<br />Tallinn performance is supported by the Norwegian Royal Embassy in Tallinn. Performances in Tallinn are presented in co-operation with Festival Baltoscandal and supported by NXTSTP, with the support of Culture Program of the European Union.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>[img] nor-engl-oh.jpg [/img] [img] NXTSTP+Euro-oh.jpg [/img]</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>[popimg] hooman-oh-06.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg]  hooman-oh-07.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] hooman-oh-01.jpg %%  Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] hooman-oh-02.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg]</p>\r\n<p>[popimg]  hooman-oh-04.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] hooman-oh-03.jpg %%  Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] hooman-oh-05.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg]  [popimg] hooman-sharifi-oh.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg]</p>',1,'','<p>Kanuti Gildi SAAL</p>\r\n<p><span class=\"suur\">HOOMAN SHARIFI</span> /NOR/ <span class=\"keskmine\">&ldquo;Lingering of an earlier event&rdquo;</span></p>');
INSERT INTO `saal_events_en` VALUES (233,'','<p>This is a new open-air version of the piece \"Bodysnatchers\" by Mihkel Ernits, a young Estonian choreographer that premiered in January on the stage of Kanuti Gildi SAAL.</p>\r\n<p><br />This visually nifty performance takes place in a scaffolding cage and can be seen on Freedom Square and on the square of Lindakivi Cultural Centre. Choreography is physical using acrobatic techniques, sometimes even dangerous - challenging the abilities of dancers. Performed by some of the most technical Estonian dancers - Rain Saukas, Laure Kvelstein, J&ouml;rgen Kapp and K&uuml;lli Roosna. Scaffolding cage hence plays the role of broadening the notion of stagespace.</p>\r\n<p><br />\"Bodysnatchers\" takes the spectators into a parallel world with its surreal characters, scaffolding cage and fanciful story. Rules and etiquette there are a mixture of that what we know of combined with overturned reality to make one think about the patterns of behaviour and rules of society. This surreal world provides young artists with a chance to test the themes that are on their minds playfully through distorting-mirror.</p>\r\n<p><br />Suitable for the whole family, but do not try this at home!</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Bodysnatchers:<br />1. Bodysnachers as tomb-breakers and organ brokers have contributed into the development of medicine throughout the history. Currently we can find examples from Thailand, Palestine and elsewhere where corpses are stolen and sold on black market.<br />2. \"The Body Snachers\" is a film based on Jack Finney science-fiction novel (1955) which describes a town in California, being invaded by seeds that have drifted to Earth from space. The seeds replace sleeping people with perfect physical duplicates. This novel has been screened 4 times and the on made in 1978 is associated with anti-communism motives (the identical ideal copies of humans as the perfect members of downright reglemented society, sowing the seeds of communism, etc).</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Mihkel Ernits</strong> is a freelance choreographer and currently he is obtaining MA degree in choreographer - director studies at Tallinn University Institute of Fine Arts Department of Choreography. In 2008 he made it to the semi final of the international contemporary dance contest C.o.n.t. est 08.<br /> <br /><strong>K&uuml;lli Roosna</strong> is a freelance dancer, who has studied choreography at Tallinn University and Rotterdam Dance Academy. She is working with various choreographers in Holland, Sweden, Norway and Estonia. She has worked with different artists, such as Dylan Newcomb, Kenneth Flak, Aida Redza, Amy Raymond, Ezequiel Sanucci, Rene N&otilde;mmik, Tiina Ollesk, J&uuml;ri Nael, Kaarel V&auml;li. As a choreographer she has created short works and assisted staging bigger projects - \"Silence\", \"My Sounds\", \"Igo\"; 2008 Music Award Gala- In April 2010 she will present her new short piece \"Keerisena Kulgemine\". K&uuml;lli teaches dance technique and improvisation as visiting lector at Tallinn University and Fine 5 Dance Theatre. http://kulliroosna.com/<br /> <br /><strong>Laura Kvelstein</strong> is a freelance dancer. She is a member of Fine 5 Dance Theatre and during the last ten years she has participated in the projects of local and international choreographers in Estonia and Holland and USA. In 2006 she was awarded with the grant of Best Young Dancer at the I.D.A dance festival in Tartu.</p>\r\n<p>Rain Saukas started dancing at Fine 5 Dance School in 2003. After two years of studying he continued as a member of Fine 5 Dance Theatre and since then he has participated at performances \"Panus\", \"Carmina Burana\", \"Reekviem\", \"Faasid\" and several other smaller projects. He earns his daily salary at design agency Taevas as graphic designer.<br /> <br /><strong>J&ouml;rgen Kapp</strong> has been top ball-room dancer; he has reached 5th place at youth world championship. He has been doing it for 12 years, since 2005 he is also a coach and judge. Right now he is simultaneously studying at the Department of Choreography at Tallinn University.<br /> <br /><strong>Maarja M&otilde;tus</strong> is a freelance designer, who currently is finishing her product design studies at the Estonian Art Academy. Previously she has been involved with fashion and costume design. She participated successfully at the Supernova fashion design contest in 2006 and she has attended workshops in Israel and Italy. In 2009 she had vocational practice with Isao Hosoe in Milan. Her curiosity towards dance got her engaged with creating the environment for this performance.</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>Idea: <strong>Mihkel Ernits</strong><br />Direction: <strong>K&uuml;lli Roosna, Mihkel Ernits</strong><br />Perfromers/choreographers: <strong>Rain Saukas, Laura Kvelstein, J&ouml;rgen Kapp, K&uuml;lli Roosna</strong><br />Light design: <strong>Revo Koplus</strong><br />Stage design: <strong>Maarja M&otilde;tus</strong><br />Music: <strong>SPK, The Fun Years, Murcof</strong><br />Sound design: <strong>Shawn Pinchbeck</strong><br />Make-up: Kaia Pihlak<br />Photos: Martin Sookael<br />Co-producer: Kanuti Gildi SAAL<br />Supporters: Cultural Endowment of Estonia, Gambling Tax Council, Metal-Disain O&Uuml;, CRAMO</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>[img] cramo-oh.jpg [/img]</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Photos: Martin Sookael</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>[popimg] m-m-oh-17.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] m-m-oh-16.jpg %%  Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] m-m-oh-1549.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg]  [popimg] m-m-oh-14.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] m-m-oh-13.jpg %%  Allkiri [/popimg]</p>\r\n<p>[popimg] m-m-oh-12.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] m-m-oh-11.jpg %%  Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] m-m-oh-10.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg]  m-m-oh-09.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] m-m-oh-08.jpg %% Allkiri  [/popimg]</p>\r\n<p>[popimg] m-m-oh-07.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] m-m-oh-06.jpg %%  Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] m-m-oh-05.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg]  m-m-oh-04.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] m-m-oh-03.jpg %% Allkiri  [/popimg]</p>\r\n<p>[popimg] m-m-oh-02.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] m-m-oh-01.jpg %%  Allkiri [/popimg]</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Photos: Elvis K&otilde;ll</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>[popimg]  kahan&auml;ppajad-elvis-k&otilde;ll-01.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg]  kehan&auml;ppajad-elvis-k&otilde;ll-02.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg]  kehan&auml;ppajad-elvis-k&otilde;ll-03.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg]  kehan&auml;ppajad-elvis-k&otilde;ll-04.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg]  kehan&auml;ppajad-elvis-k&otilde;ll-05.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg]</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>NB!</p>\r\n<p><strong>16.08 / 21:00 in cinema Artis</strong> within the frames of the special program Exclusively for Freaks:<br /><strong>\"ISADORA\" / dir. KAREL REISZ</strong><br />more info: <a href=\"http://www.kino.ee/index.php?page=1551&amp;\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.kino.ee/index.php?page=1551&amp;</a></p>\r\n<p><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> <w:WordDocument> <w:View>Normal</w:View> <w:Zoom>0</w:Zoom> <w:HyphenationZone>21</w:HyphenationZone> <w:PunctuationKerning /> <w:ValidateAgainstSchemas /> <w:SaveIfXMLInvalid>false</w:SaveIfXMLInvalid> <w:IgnoreMixedContent>false</w:IgnoreMixedContent> <w:AlwaysShowPlaceholderText>false</w:AlwaysShowPlaceholderText> <w:Compatibility> <w:BreakWrappedTables /> <w:SnapToGridInCell /> <w:WrapTextWithPunct /> <w:UseAsianBreakRules /> <w:DontGrowAutofit /> </w:Compatibility> <w:BrowserLevel>MicrosoftInternetExplorer4</w:BrowserLevel> </w:WordDocument> </xml><![endif]--><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> <w:LatentStyles DefLockedState=\"false\" LatentStyleCount=\"156\"> </w:LatentStyles> </xml><![endif]--><!--[if !mso]> \r\n<object  classid=\"clsid:38481807-CA0E-42D2-BF39-B33AF135CC4D\" id=ieooui>\r\n</object>\r\n<mce:style><!  st1\\:*{behavior:url(#ieooui) } --> <!--[endif]--> <!--  /* Style Definitions */  p.MsoNormal, li.MsoNormal, div.