INSERT INTO `saal_events_en` VALUES (234,'','<p>In June 2010, a new generation of dancers and choreographers finished their studies at P.A.R.T.S. (Performing Arts Research and Training Studios), the school for contemporary dance founded and directed by one of the most known choreographers of our time Anne Teresa De Keersmaeker in Brussels. 24 students from 12 countries and 5 continents end their 4-year training with a series of personal creations and a repertoire project, presented to the audience during an international tour. 12 of them will be present in Tallinn.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>In Tallinn they present two different programs.<br />The first program is a remake of Anne Teresa De Keersmaeker\'s Drumming (originally from 1998), a core work from her repertoire that marries dance with the compelling rhythmical music of Steve Reich, a complex choreography built around a simple dance phrase. The students have revived the original choreography in an intensive 3-month work period.</p>\r\n<p><br />Drumming was created in August 1998 to a composition of Steve Reich. The compelling rhythmicality of the music propels the dancers into a choreography that appears complex and at the same time insidiously simple. Just like the music, the dance proceeds from a single motion phrase, explored exhaustively and unremittingly for an hour through endless combinations, variations and transformations, by reversing it, speeding it up and slowing it down.<br />For three months, the students worked on a new version, recreating the original piece with some ariations, directed by former dancers of Rosas under the guidance of Anne Teresa De Keersmaeker herself.</p>\r\n<p>PARTS was founded by Rosas and De Munt/ La Monnaie. The school is funded by the Ministry of education of the Flemish Government and receives additional support of De Munt/ La Monnaie, the National Lottery and the network d&eacute;parts. d&eacute;parts is funded by the European Commission (Culture program).</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>Choreography:<strong> Anne Teresa De Keersmaeker</strong> (1998)<br />Music: <strong>Steve Reich</strong>, &lsquo;Drumming\'<br />Project directors: <strong>Marta Coronado, Jakub Truszkowski </strong><br />Dancers:  <strong>Salka Ardal Rosengren, Fanny Brouyaux, Anneleen Keppens, Cecilia Lisa  Eliceche, Steven Michel, Anne Pajunen, Jonathan Pranlas, Marco Torrice,  Petra Van Gompel, Anna K. Whaley, Stav Yeini, Elisa Yvelin</strong><br />Lights: <strong>Wannes Dereydt </strong><br />Production: Martine Lange<br />Technicians: Wannes Dereydt, Ise Debrouwere<br />Thanks to Anne-Cath&eacute;rine Kunz for help with the costumes.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.parts.be\" target=\"_blank\">www.parts.be</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>[popimg] drumming-oh-02.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] drumming-oh-03.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] drumming-oh-04.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] drumming-oh-01.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg]</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>NB!</p>\r\n<p><strong>16.08 / 21:00 in cinema Artis</strong> within the frames of the special program Exclusively for Freaks:<br /><strong>\"ISADORA\" / dir. KAREL REISZ</strong><br />more info: <a href=\"http://www.kino.ee/index.php?page=1551&amp;\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.kino.ee/index.php?page=1551&amp;</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',1,'','<p>Theatre NO99</p>\r\n<p><span class=\"suur\"> </span></p>\r\n<p><span class=\"suur\">P.A.R.T.S. / ANNE TERESA DE KEERSMAEKER</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"pisike\">/BELGIUM/ </span><span class=\"keskmine\">\"RE: Drumming\"</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>');
INSERT INTO `saal_events_en` VALUES (235,'','<p>In June 2010, a new generation of dancers and choreographers finished their studies at P.A.R.T.S. (Performing Arts Research and Training Studios), the school for contemporary dance founded and directed by one of the most known choreographers of our time Anne Teresa De Keersmaeker in Brussels. 24 students from 12 countries and 5 continents end their 4-year training with a series of personal creations and a repertoire project, presented to the audience during an international tour. 12 of them will be present in Tallinn.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>In Tallinn they present two different programs.<br />The second program presents a selection of the own creations of the students. Solo or in small groups, these works are as diverse as contemporary dance can be, intimate or exuberant, visceral or cerebral, loud or quiet - and often balancing in between. They are all the result of a personal research without boundaries, the first public steps of the fresh faces of dance.</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>JONATHAN PRANLAS</strong> /FRA/ <strong>&amp; PETRA VAN GOMPEL</strong> /BEL/ \"It\'s not what but how...\"</span></p>\r\n<p><br />Driven with a stubborn will, the performers have a total commitment into action to create the choreography.<br />The piece relies on random principles to search for something concrete into the movement. <br />Acknowledging physicality as dance.<br /> <br />Every action is twisted with a certain human absurdity. Playing upside-down. Pushing endlessly. Over-singing the background...  <br />At one point being organized. Creating a raft in space. <br />With what\'s left, maybe just eat it!\r\n<hr />\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Choreography: <strong>Jonathan Pranlas with Petra Van Gompel</strong><br />Performance: <strong>Petra Van Gompel &amp; Jonathan Pranlas</strong><br />Coach: <strong>Chrysa Parkinson </strong><br />Music : <strong>Wagner </strong>/ Tristan und Iseult<br />Duration: 25&acute;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>[popimg] parts-oh-02.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] parts-oh-03.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg]</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>ANNE PAJUNEN</strong> /FIN/ \"The Man\"</span></p>\r\n<p><br />The Man is a peep into the life of one person, one character. It&acute;s a meeting; The man represents himself, allows himself to be seen and arouses the question, who is he? The surface suggests a clear identity, but what kinds of things can appear from underneath the disguise if we allow our gazes to dig deeper?\r\n<hr />\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Choreography and Performance: <strong>Anne Pajunen </strong><br />Coaching: ( and big thanks!!! ) <strong>Eleanor Bauer, Lucy Grauman</strong><br />Music: <strong>Jacob Gade, Jealousy Tango, Juha Vainio, Kotkan poikii ilman siipii</strong><br />Duration: 20&acute;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>[popimg] parts-oh-04.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] parts-oh-05.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg]</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><br /><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>VELI LEHTOVAARA </strong>/FIN/<strong> &amp; STAV YEINI</strong> /ISR/ \"A standing man behind a seated woman\"</span> (film)</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\"A standing man behind a seated woman\" was created by Veli Lehtovaara(FL) and Stav Yeini (IL) during their studies in the research cycle at P.A.R.T.S in spring 2009.The film is based on a short story written by the Israeli author Hanoch Levin. The multiple story tellers reflect upon a picture of a man standing behind a woman in a closed, unrecognizable space. The picture is transforming into a moving image which is constantly adjusting itself as the story goes on. The composition of sound and image create a dialogue between auditive and visual information. These two layers are sometimes synchronized and other times independent with unexpected consequences. The film won the audience prize in \"idill\" - international dance on line film festival 2009.\r\n<hr />\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Direction, performance, editing: <strong>Veli Lehtovaara &amp; Stav Yeini</strong><br />Technical support and assistance: <strong>Stanislav Dobak</strong><br />Coach: <strong>Thierry De Mey</strong><br />Thanks to: Charleroi/danses-La Raffinerie for space and technical help<br />Duration: 12&acute;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>STEVEN MICHEL</strong> /FRA/ \"The desert of milestones\"</span></p>\r\n<p><br />The desert of milestones  is a journey through rhythmical aspects of narrative. The creation of this solo started with the idea of composing scores of body rhythms that can transform into meanings and events. Giving priority to the soundscape and its \"re-percussions\" on action, The desert of milestones  is a rhythmical morphing of episodic imagery.\r\n<hr />\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Choreography and performance: <strong>Steven Michel</strong><br />Coaching: <strong>Chrysa Parkinson, Thomas Hauert</strong><br />Duration: 20&acute;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>[popimg] parts-oh-01.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg]</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>CECILIA LISA ELICECHE</strong> /ARG/ <strong>&amp; ELISA YVELIN</strong> /FRA/ \"The Time Lapse Opera\"</span></p>\r\n<p><br />A work based on the tension of two bodies in space and the accumulation of dramatic elements.<br />Two hot subjects in a cold frame.\r\n<hr />\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Choreography and performance:<strong> Cecilia Lisa Eliceche &amp; Elisa Yvelin</strong><br />Music: <strong>Michael Nyman, Time lapse </strong><br />Costumes: <strong>Cecilia Lisa Eliceche </strong><br />Singing coach:<strong> Lucy Grauman</strong><br />Coach:<strong> Mark Vanrunxt</strong><br />Thanks to: Jan Ritsema, Eleanor Bauer, Steven De Belder, Tom Pauwels<br />Duration: 25&acute;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>PARTS </strong>was founded by Rosas and De Munt/ La Monnaie. The school is funded by the Ministry of education of the Flemish Government and receives additional support of De Munt/ La Monnaie, the National Lottery and the network d&eacute;parts. d&eacute;parts is funded by the European Commission (Culture program).</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>Production: Martine Lange<br />Light design: Joris De Bolle<br />Technicians: Ise Debrouwere, Wannes Dereydt</p>\r\n<p>Photo: Bart Grietens<br />Duration: 25\' + 20\' + 12&acute;+ 20\' + 25\'<br /><a href=\"http://www.parts.be\">www.parts.be</a></p>',1,'','<p>Theatre NO99<br /><span class=\"suur\">P.A.R.T.S.</span> /BEL/: <span class=\"keskmine\">personal work</span></p>');
INSERT INTO `saal_events_en` VALUES (236,'','<p>In 2010 August DanceFestival is dedicated primarily to the future names of the dance scene and this evening presents three young Estonian choreographers. They all have graduated from University of Tartu Viljandi Culture Academy. The way they look at dance is fascinatingly different. They are searching for new forms and themes in a more radical way, and humour is a part of it. Future is in front of you !</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>ELE VISKUS</strong> \"Taidlusr&uuml;hm R&auml;hn\"</span><br />Idea, choreography: Ele Viskus<br />Dance: Karl Saks, T&otilde;nis Niinemets, Ele Viskus<br />Tutor: Raido M&auml;gi<br />Costume aid: Kadri Vaas <br /> Photo: Merli Antsmaa<br />Music: Aux 88 ,Venetian Snares, Broken Time Orchestra, Angerfist<br />Duration: 25\'</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>[popimg] ele-oh-01.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] ele-oh-02.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] ele-oh-03.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] ele-oh-04.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg]</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>LIIS ILULA</strong> \"&auml;lis mnimedemaal\"</span><br />Choreography: Liis Ilula<br />Dance: Arolin Raudva, Liis Vares, Jaanus Tepomees, T&otilde;nis Niinemets</p>\r\n<p>Light, animation: Luise Leesment<br />Music: Massive Attack, Toomas Savi<br />Thanks to: Helje Ilula, Riin K&otilde;iv, Roland Leesment, Tartu &Uuml;likooli Viljandi Kultuuriakadeemia, Kanuti Gildi SAAL, Eesti Kultuurkapital, Eesti Nuku- ja Noorsooteater<br />Duration: 20\'</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>[popimg] liis-oh-01.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] liis-oh-02.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] liis-oh-04.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] liis-oh-05.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg]</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>HENRI H&Uuml;TT</strong> \"The Reader\"</span><br />Idea, direction: Henri H&uuml;tt<br />On stage: Mihkel Ilus, Henri H&uuml;tt<br />Sound: Roland Karlson<br />Design: Mihkel Ilus<br />Video: Henri H&uuml;tt<br />Light: Villu Konrad<br />Direction aid: Raido M&auml;gi<br />Technological aid, costume, photo: Kaie Olmre-H&uuml;tt<br />Duration: 30\'</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>[popimg] henri-oh-01.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] henri-oh-02.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] henri-oh-03.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] henri-oh-04.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg]</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',1,'','<p>Kanuti Gildi SAAL</p>\r\n<p><span class=\"suur\">ELE VISKUS</span><span class=\"suur\"> + LIIS ILULA + </span><span class=\"suur\">HENRI H&Uuml;TT</span> /EST/</p>');
INSERT INTO `saal_events_en` VALUES (237,'','<p>This is a new open-air version of the piece \"Bodysnatchers\" by Mihkel  Ernits, a young Estonian choreographer that premiered in January on the  stage of Kanuti Gildi SAAL.</p>\r\n<p><br />This visually nifty performance takes place in a scaffolding cage  and can be seen on Freedom Square and on the square of Lindakivi  Cultural Centre. Choreography is physical using acrobatic techniques,  sometimes even dangerous - challenging the abilities of dancers.  Performed by some of the most technical Estonian dancers - Rain Saukas,  Laure Kvelstein, J&ouml;rgen Kapp and K&uuml;lli Roosna. Scaffolding cage hence  plays the role of broadening the notion of stagespace.</p>\r\n<p><br />\"Bodysnatchers\" takes the spectators into a parallel world with  its surreal characters, scaffolding cage and fanciful story. Rules and  etiquette there are a mixture of that what we know of combined with  overturned reality to make one think about the patterns of behaviour and  rules of society. This surreal world provides young artists with a  chance to test the themes that are on their minds playfully through  distorting-mirror.</p>\r\n<p><br />Suitable for the whole family, but do not try this at home!</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Bodysnatchers:<br />1. Bodysnachers as tomb-breakers and organ brokers  have contributed into the development of medicine throughout the  history. Currently we can find examples from Thailand, Palestine and  elsewhere where corpses are stolen and sold on black market.<br />2. \"The  Body Snachers\" is a film based on Jack Finney science-fiction novel  (1955) which describes a town in California, being invaded by seeds that  have drifted to Earth from space. The seeds replace sleeping people  with perfect physical duplicates. This novel has been screened 4 times  and the on made in 1978 is associated with anti-communism motives (the  identical ideal copies of humans as the perfect members of downright  reglemented society, sowing the seeds of communism, etc).</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Mihkel Ernits</strong> is a freelance choreographer and currently he is  obtaining MA degree in choreographer - director studies at Tallinn  University Institute of Fine Arts Department of Choreography. In 2008 he  made it to the semi final of the international contemporary dance  contest C.o.n.t. est 08.<br /> <br /><strong>K&uuml;lli Roosna</strong> is a freelance  dancer, who has studied choreography at Tallinn University and Rotterdam  Dance Academy. She is working with various choreographers in Holland,  Sweden, Norway and Estonia. She has worked with different artists, such  as Dylan Newcomb, Kenneth Flak, Aida Redza, Amy Raymond, Ezequiel  Sanucci, Rene N&otilde;mmik, Tiina Ollesk, J&uuml;ri Nael, Kaarel V&auml;li. As a  choreographer she has created short works and assisted staging bigger  projects - \"Silence\", \"My Sounds\", \"Igo\"; 2008 Music Award Gala- In  April 2010 she will present her new short piece \"Keerisena Kulgemine\".  K&uuml;lli teaches dance technique and improvisation as visiting lector at  Tallinn University and Fine 5 Dance Theatre. http://kulliroosna.com/<br /> <br /><strong>Laura Kvelstein</strong> is a freelance dancer. She is a member of  Fine 5 Dance Theatre and during the last ten years she has participated  in the projects of local and international choreographers in Estonia and  Holland and USA. In 2006 she was awarded with the grant of Best Young  Dancer at the I.D.A dance festival in Tartu.</p>\r\n<p>Rain Saukas started dancing at Fine 5 Dance School in 2003. After two  years of studying he continued as a member of Fine 5 Dance Theatre and  since then he has participated at performances \"Panus\", \"Carmina  Burana\", \"Reekviem\", \"Faasid\" and several other smaller projects. He  earns his daily salary at design agency Taevas as graphic designer.<br /> <br /><strong>J&ouml;rgen  Kapp</strong> has been top ball-room dancer; he has reached 5th place at  youth world championship. He has been doing it for 12 years, since 2005  he is also a coach and judge. Right now he is simultaneously studying at  the Department of Choreography at Tallinn University.<br /> <br /><strong>Maarja  M&otilde;tus</strong> is a freelance designer, who currently is finishing her  product design studies at the Estonian Art Academy. Previously she has  been involved with fashion and costume design. She participated  successfully at the Supernova fashion design contest in 2006 and she has  attended workshops in Israel and Italy. In 2009 she had vocational  practice with Isao Hosoe in Milan. Her curiosity towards dance got her  engaged with creating the environment for this performance.</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>Idea: <strong>Mihkel Ernits</strong><br />Direction: <strong>K&uuml;lli Roosna, Mihkel  Ernits</strong><br />Perfromers/choreographers: <strong>Rain Saukas, Laura  Kvelstein, J&ouml;rgen Kapp, K&uuml;lli Roosna</strong><br />Light design: <strong>Revo Koplus</strong><br />Stage  design: <strong>Maarja M&otilde;tus</strong><br />Music: <strong>SPK, The Fun Years, Murcof</strong><br />Sound  design: <strong>Shawn Pinchbeck</strong><br />Make-up: Kaia Pihlak<br />Photos:  Martin Sookael<br />Co-producer: Kanuti Gildi SAAL<br />Supporters: Cultural  Endowment of Estonia, Gambling Tax Council, Metal-Disain O&Uuml;, CRAMO</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>[img] cramo-oh.jpg [/img]</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>[popimg] m-m-oh-17.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] m-m-oh-16.jpg %%  Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] m-m-oh-1549.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg]  [popimg] m-m-oh-14.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] m-m-oh-13.jpg %%  Allkiri [/popimg]</p>\r\n<p>[popimg] m-m-oh-12.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] m-m-oh-11.jpg %%  Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] m-m-oh-10.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg]  m-m-oh-09.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] m-m-oh-08.jpg %% Allkiri  [/popimg]</p>\r\n<p>[popimg] m-m-oh-07.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] m-m-oh-06.jpg %%  Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] m-m-oh-05.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg]  m-m-oh-04.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] m-m-oh-03.jpg %% Allkiri  [/popimg]</p>\r\n<p>[popimg] m-m-oh-02.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] m-m-oh-01.jpg %%  Allkiri [/popimg]</p>',1,'','<p>Lindakivi Cultural Centre Square</p>\r\n<p><span class=\"suur\">MIHKEL ERNITS</span> /EST/ <span class=\"keskmine\">\"Bodysnatchers\"</span></p>');
INSERT INTO `saal_events_en` VALUES (238,'','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Choreographer-dancer Mart Kangro and composer-musician Taavi Kerikm&auml;e try in their production \"Harmony\" together with Ensemble U: to delve on the paradoxes of professional music interprets. What are musicians actually doing while performing music? What do they do and think while waiting for their five bars of solo during a long suite? Is this inescapable silence comic or even tragic in nature? Quite a bundle of paradoxes and it takes Kerikm&auml;e, Ensemble U: and Kangro to sort it out, together with a tad of tongue-in-cheek.<br /> <br />Possibly one of the most internationally acclaimed Estonian contemporary choreographers Mart Kangro has created 8 full-length dance pieces that have been presented in more than 20 countries all over Europe and North America.</p>\r\n<p>Taavi Kerikm&auml;e is a composer and a musician. Together with Mart Soo he curates a series of concerts of contemporary improvisational music Improtest at Kanuti Gildi SAAL. He has studied music in Tallinn and Lyon. He gives lectures at the Estonian Academy of Music and Theatre.<br /> <br />Ensemble U: is a group of musicians performing contemporary music founded in 2002 by Taavi Kerikm&auml;e and Tarmo Johannes.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>Idea &amp; direction: Taavi Kerikm&auml;e, Mart Kangro<br />Ensemble U: Tarmo Johannes, Merje Roomere, Levi-Danel M&auml;gila, Helena Tuuling, Vambola Krigul, Taavi Kerikm&auml;e<br />Music: A.Sch&ouml;nberg, S.Prokofjev, K.Kuitunen, C.Carson Parks, Doors, P.Simon, A.Garfunkel, J.Livingston, R. Evans, M.Leander, R. Rannap, W.A. Mozart<br />Technical realisation: Kalle Tikas<br />Photo: Harri Rospu<br />Co-producers NYYD festival, Kanuti Gildi SAAL<br />Supporter: Cultural Endowment of Estonia<br />Duration: 60&acute;<br /><a href=\"http://uuu.ee/\" target=\"_blank\">http://uuu.ee/</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>[popimg] u-oh-01.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] u-oh-02.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] u-oh-03.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg]</p>',1,'','<p>Kanuti Gildi SAAL<br /><span class=\"suur\">MART KANGRO &amp; ANSAMBEL U:</span> /EST/ <span class=\"keskmine\">\"Harmoonia\"</span></p>');
INSERT INTO `saal_events_en` VALUES (239,'','<p>Two young dancers and choreographers from Spanish Galicia, Alexis Fern&aacute;ndez and Caterina Varela, are extraordinarily profound and connected in their piece \"VEN\" what the audience can see on the two locations in the Tallinn centre. It is a perfect interplay which fascinates and surprises. It\'s as though they defy the laws of physics. This piece was premiered in La Habana in March 2008 and since then toured intensively throughout the world.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\"a shocking choreography of great beauty, accompanied by a moving music which makes it feel like a \"living video clip.\"\"</p>\r\n<p>(Spanish cultural magazine, El Cultural)</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\"\"VEN\" has caught the audience from the very first moment and kept the tension in them until the last movement. Flawless execution.\"</p>\r\n<p>(Spanish dance magazine, Danza Eter)</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Alexis Fern&aacute;ndez</strong> was born on Cuba. He graduated of the Nacional School of Arts in La Habana. He has been part of different dance companies, such as: Danza Contempor&aacute;nea de Cuba, Grupo Pulsar (Brazil), Danza Retazos (Cuba), Experimentadanza (Spain), Memory Wax (Sweden), La Intrusa (Spain) or Centro Coreogr&aacute;fico Galego (Spain). Founder of the company Entremans (Spain) in 2006 and founder of the company La Macana (Spain) in 2009.<br />He has performance in several festivals in Cuba, Brazil, Venezuela, Ecuador, France, Spain, Denmark, Holland, Germany, Italy, Luxembourg, England, Portugal, Belgium, Sweden and Switzerland.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Spanish choreographer and dancer <strong>Caterina Varela</strong> has been member of several companies such as Experimentadanza (Spain) and the Centro Coreogr&aacute;fico Galego (Spain). She is part of the company Entremans (Spain) since 2007. Founder of the company La Macana (Spain) in 2009. She has performance in several festivals in Spain, Portugal, Sweden, Belgium, Cuba, Germany, Italy, Luxembourg and France.</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Creation and interpretation:<strong> Alexis Fern&aacute;ndez and Caterina Varela</strong><br />Music: <strong>Einst&uuml;rzende Neubauten</strong><br />Production: La Macana<br />Tallinn performances are supported by Embassy of Spain in Estonia.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.blogdelamacana.blogspot.com\" target=\"_blank\">www.blogdelamacana.blogspot.com</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>[img] hisp-stk-oh.jpg [/img]</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>[popimg]  lamacana-oh-01.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] lamacana-oh-02.jpg %%  Allkiri [/popimg]</p>',1,'','<p>Tammsaare Park<br /><span class=\"suur\">LA MACANA</span> /ESP/ <span class=\"keskmine\">\"VEN\"</span></p>');
INSERT INTO `saal_events_en` VALUES (240,'','<p>Two young dancers and choreographers from Spanish Galicia, Alexis Fern&aacute;ndez and Caterina Varela, are extraordinarily profound and connected in their piece \"VEN\" what the audience can see on the two locations in the Tallinn centre. It is a perfect interplay which fascinates and surprises. It\'s as though they defy the laws of physics. This piece was premiered in La Habana in March 2008 and since then toured intensively throughout the world.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\"a shocking choreography of great beauty, accompanied by a moving music which makes it feel like a \"living video clip.\"\"</p>\r\n<p>(Spanish cultural magazine, El Cultural)</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\"\"VEN\" has caught the audience from the very first moment and kept the tension in them until the last movement. Flawless execution.\"</p>\r\n<p>(Spanish dance magazine, Danza Eter)</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Alexis Fern&aacute;ndez</strong> was born on Cuba. He graduated of the Nacional School of Arts in La Habana. He has been part of different dance companies, such as: Danza Contempor&aacute;nea de Cuba, Grupo Pulsar (Brazil), Danza Retazos (Cuba), Experimentadanza (Spain), Memory Wax (Sweden), La Intrusa (Spain) or Centro Coreogr&aacute;fico Galego (Spain). Founder of the company Entremans (Spain) in 2006 and founder of the company La Macana (Spain) in 2009.<br />He has performance in several festivals in Cuba, Brazil, Venezuela, Ecuador, France, Spain, Denmark, Holland, Germany, Italy, Luxembourg, England, Portugal, Belgium, Sweden and Switzerland.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Spanish choreographer and dancer <strong>Caterina Varela</strong> has been member of several companies such as Experimentadanza (Spain) and the Centro Coreogr&aacute;fico Galego (Spain). She is part of the company Entremans (Spain) since 2007. Founder of the company La Macana (Spain) in 2009. She has performance in several festivals in Spain, Portugal, Sweden, Belgium, Cuba, Germany, Italy, Luxembourg and France.</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Creation and interpretation:<strong> Alexis Fern&aacute;ndez and Caterina Varela</strong><br />Music: <strong>Einst&uuml;rzende Neubauten</strong><br />Production: La Macana<br />Tallinn performances are supported by Embassy of Spain in Estonia.</p>\r\n<p>www.blogdelamacana.blogspot.com</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>[img] hisp-stk-oh.jpg [/img]</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>[popimg]  lamacana-oh-01.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] lamacana-oh-02.jpg %%  Allkiri [/popimg]</p>',1,'','<p>Cinema S&otilde;prus Square<br /><span class=\"suur\">LA MACANA</span> /ESP/ <span class=\"keskmine\">\"VEN\"</span></p>');
INSERT INTO `saal_events_en` VALUES (241,'','<p>Vava &#350;tef&#259;nescu has been visible on the dance and performance scene for several years. Her original and research based works have caught attention over the world. \"Quartet for a Microphone\" is a real time sound and choreographic installation inspired by a phone booth stanging on stage. This work sets a discourse about confinement, the lack of distance, the relation with the other and about the idea of being hostages of our own existence. Being a real time composition the only reference and support is set on the visible/audible situation that is constant during 60 minutes. Every idea -sort of starting-point keywords- come into conjunction with the movement of sound, with the glance of the audience and this is how other new and unexpected ideas are born. For Vava Stefanescu, the accidental of the presence conditioned by this specific context, the attention for perception rituals, are constant preoccupations but also fascinations about this \"come and go\" between fiction and reality.</p>\r\n<p><strong><br /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Vava Stef&#259;nescu</strong> is a choreographer and dancer, living and working in Romania. She is Artistic Director of CNDB. In 1994, she graduated from the Choreography Department of the National University of Drama and Film in Bucharest and in 2004 the MA in International Artistic Cooperation at Paris 8, UFR Arts. Her performances were presented on national and international stages (London, Leipzig, D&uuml;sseldorf, Hamburg, Hanover, Paris, Sofia, Poland, Japan...) Her most recent creations are Solo On-Line, Mioritza- choreographic installation, A Hot Summer On Iza, Quartet For A Microphone, Getto Blaster, 3 dances of Beckett. She creates choreography and performs for theater: the Forgetting (G. Banu), the Jewish Trilogy, Perls Fishers , Song of the Songs, Julieta (Viski Andr&aacute;s), directed or in authoshipwith Mihai M&#259;niu&#355;iu; \"the Long Friday\" (Viski Andr&aacute;s).<br />In 2000, she founded Multi-Art-Dans Centre - MAD, an independent institution for supporting choreographers and dancers and multidisciplinary artistic creation. From 1994 to 2001, Vava &#350;tef&#259;nescu teaches contemporary dance at the Choreography High School in Bucharest and university assistant at the Choreography Department of the National University of Drama and Film in Bucharest. Currently she leads workshops of choreographic composition in the framework of festivals and artistic residences.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Julien Trambouze</strong> is radio producer journalist, reporter and documentary producer for Radio France.  In 2009 he wins the price the best radio series documentary for \"Bonne F&ecirc;te la Mere\", Strasbourg, Radio France and have high rating audience for \"200 ans de Guignol\" as for \"Sex Call - pour t\'exciter &agrave; fond\" produced by ARTE RADIO. From 2002 to 2006 he was artistic director of Centrifuj a venue for performance, concert and art exhibitions in Valence, France.  As sound designer he works for choreography with Vava Stefanescu for Quartet for a Microphone (2008) and Getto Blaster (2009) and with Carmen Cotofana and Mihaela Dancs, in creation residency in the framework of Jardin d\'Europe. In theater he creates the sound for  \"Odihna \", directed by Mihai Maniutiu, and for  the installation \"multiplex\" with Gianina Carbunariu. He also signs the sound for the performance <br />\"love from lu\", directed by Luiza Mogosanu at gallery Heliumcowboy Artspace Hamburg, and is co-author for the sound piece \"Call Me / cadavre exquis t&eacute;l&eacute;phonique\" with Nathalie Rubens,(2005).</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Carmen Cotofan&#259;</strong> graduated from the Octavian Stroia Choreography High school and the Choreography Department of the National University of Drama and Film in Bucharest. She participated in workshops with Pal Frenak, Karine Saporta, Donna Uchizono, Mark Tompkins, Carol Brawn, David Zambrano, Vera Mantero, Xavier le Roy. She collaborated with choreographers Sorana Badea, Mihai Mihalcea, Valentina de Piante, Charles Lineham, Florin Fieroiu, Ioana Macarie, C&#259;t&#259;lina Gubandru, Vava &#350;tef&#259;nescu, Eduard Gabia, M&#259;d&#259;lina Dan, and theater directors Gianina C&#259;rbunariu, Andreea V&#259;lean, Alexandru Dabija, Radu Nica. Personal creations: BEINGS OF HANDS; TAKE FIVE; STEP FORWARD; FREE MESH; RECYCLE ME and co-author for FIRST STEPS, premiered at Explore Dance Festival (Bucharest), in October 2009.</p>\r\n<p>Farid Fairuz was born in Beirut to a Lebanese mother and a Jewish father. During his life he was marked by the troubling love story between his parents who lived clandestinely for 10 years always migrating between Turkey, Syria, Lebanon and Jordan. After their tragic disappearance during the Beirut war he is adopted by two Bedouins who feed him camel milk and educate him according to their beliefs. Fairuz has a different behavior than the other children his age and he proves to be extremely sensitive. The destiny smiles upon him when, aged 11, he is adopted by a rich Jordanian family which treats his studies with great care. Thus Farid Fairuz ends up studying the music of Arab peoples, oriental dance, classic and contemporary dance, and then he creates performances and dances for a few years in Europe and United States of America being regarded as a curiosity.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>M&#259;d&#259;lina Dan</strong> graduated the University for Drama and Film, Dance Department in Bucharest. From 1998 to 2003 she is a member of \"Oleg Danovski\" Dance Company, Constanta.<br />In 2008 participates to DanceWeb Scholarship-Wien. Collaborates as dancer or co-author with choreographers Cosmin Manolescu, Vava &#350;tef&#259;nescu, Gigi C&#259;ciuleanu, Sergiu Anghel, Alexandra Pirici, Lisa Naugle, Christine Bastin, Pierr Wiss &#351;i Jean Guizerix. <br />She participates to workshops lead by Martin Sonderkamp, Lin Snelling, Andrew Harwood, Lisa Race, Keith Hennessy, Judith Grodowitz, Libby Farr, Rasmus Olme, Olive Bieringa, Ko Murobushi, Paolo Enrique, Margarida Bettencourt, Laura Simi, Damiano Foa, Donna Uchizona, Christine Bastin, Ivan Wolf, Milli Biterli, Mark Tompkins, Lisa Naugle, Florin Fieroiu, Judith Turros, Daniel Meja, Erwin Kecsek &#351;i Wilfride Piollet. <br />Her own creations were presented in many festivals or venues in Romania or abroad:  Just like a woman\", &bdquo;Need for speed\", &bdquo;Dedublarea\", &bdquo;Iluzionistele\",  \"Beginning, Middle, End\", in collaboration with Andrea Bozic (Croatia/Holland) and Michael Pinchbeck (Great Britain).</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>Concept/ author: <strong>Vava &#350;tef&#259;nescu</strong><br />Co-authors: <strong>Julien Trambouze </strong>(sound artist),<strong> Carmen Co&#355;ofan&#259;, M&#259;d&#259;lina Dan, Farid Fairuz </strong>(performers)</p>\r\n<p>Photos: Irina Stelea</p>\r\n<p>Set design sponsor: MAGNUM<br />Sponsor: Liternet<br />With the support of AFCN Romania<br />Duration: 60&acute;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>[popimg] vava-oh-01.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] vava-oh-02.jpg  %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] vava-oh-03.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg]  [popimg] vava-oh-04.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] vava-oh-05.jpg %%  Allkiri [/popimg]</p>\r\n<p>[popimg] vava-oh-06.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg]  [popimg] vava-oh-0656.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg]</p>',1,'','<p>Von Krahl Theatre<br /><span class=\"suur\">VAVA STEFANESCU</span> /ROM/ <span class=\"keskmine\">\"Quartet for a microphone\"</span></p>');
INSERT INTO `saal_events_en` VALUES (242,'','<p>This year the festival will end with a not-very-serious nostalgic trip.</p>\r\n<p><br />\"MADE IN RUSSIA\" is the latest project of Russian dancer Andrei Andrianov and choreographer Oleg Soulimenko. Finally, they are revealing their so far strictly confidential relationships with two famous characters of the European and Russian art scene: French filmmaker Jean-Luc Godard as the intellectual super-father from the West and the flagship prima ballerina Maya Plisetskaya, highly appreciated by the Soviet regime, play essential roles. Andrianov and Soulimenko reflect on their ever-changing artistic and personal development through songs, stories and styles of dancing. Post-communist war battle of eastern and western cultural clich&eacute;s.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>In 1993 Russian dancer Andrei Andrianov and choreographer Oleg Soulimenko founded a dance-performance duo under the name of Saira Blanche Theatre. The duo performed on various festivals in the cities of Vienna, Moscow, Amsterdam, Berlin, New York, Yaroslavl, Yekaterinburg, Greifswald, Potsdam, Stockholm, Brunswick, Tallinn and many more. After a longer lasting break, Andrei Andrianov and Oleg Soulimenko resumed their collaborative work in May 2007.</p>\r\n<p><strong><br /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Andrei Andrianov </strong>is a dancer, choreographer and teacher. He began his career in 1979 at Gedrus Mackjavichus\' Modern Dance and Mime Theatre in Moscow. He learned modern dance, pantomime, improvisation, martial arts and acting. Later on in Europe he also studied contact improvisation, BMC, release techniques and performance art. In 1993, together with Oleg Soulimenko, Andrianov created the dance-performance duo for Saira Blanche Theatre. From 1996 to 2000 he was regularly collaborating with the Vienna-based performance ensemble Lux Flux. In 2001, Andrianov was engaged as a dancer by the newly founded company Do-Dance at the Moscow Theatre School of Dramatic Art. In 2003, he was the choreographer in residence at Vienna\'s Tanzquartier Wien where he presented a new solo for the \"Factory Season\". In April 2008, the piece \"Burnashev &amp; Andrianov (live)\" premiered in Moscow under his direction.</p>\r\n<p><strong><br /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Oleg Soulimenko</strong> is a Russian performer and choreographer living and working in Vienna. In 1985, he graduated from Bauman Moscow State Technical University with a degree in construction engineering and decided to become a dancer. In 1991, he founded the Saira Blanche Theatre, developing a sophisticated and provocative form of dance improvisation. Soulimenko has collaborated with artists like Steve Paxton, Lisa Nelson, Markus Schinwald, Meg Stuart &amp; Damaged Goods, Lebbeus Woods, and Jennifer Lacey. His latest performances were presented in eastern and western Europe, in the USA, in Canada, in Israel, at the Tanzquartier and at brut theatre in Vienna, at Performa 07 in New York, at steirischer herbst in Graz, at Tangente in Montreal, at Cankarjev Dom in Ljubljana, at the Dostoyevsky Theatre in St. Petersburg, at the Jerusalem Gerard bercher Center, at the Kunstverein Hannover, at the MAK - Museum for Applied Arts in Vienna, at the Lentos Arts Museum in Linz, and at the Kunsthalle Wien.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Maya Plisetskaya</strong>, born in 1925 in Moscow, descends from a Russian family with a long ballet tradition, her uncle being a legendary ballet instructor, her aunt a prima ballerina at the Bolshoi. Her teenage years were shaped by the Stalinist purges with her father disappearing without a trace in 1937. \"The Dying Swan\" became her calling card: more than twenty thousand times did she dance \"her\" role. She embodied all classical main parts like the Laurentia in the eponymous ballet by Krejn, as well as the Juliet in \"Romeo and Juliet\". She last performed in 1996 at the age of 71.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Jean-Luc Godard</strong> was born in Paris in 1930 into an upper-class French-Swiss family. During his studies of ethnology at Sorbonne University he made contact with a Parisian film club also joined by Fran&ccedil;ois Truffaut, Jacques Rivette and &Eacute;ric Rohmer. When in 1951 Andr&eacute; Bazin founded the critical magazine Cahiers du Cin&eacute;ma, Godard was among its first authors. He is known as the most innovative, most productive and most debated director of the \"Nouvelle Vague\". In his films, Godard does not mirror, but cite and assemble reality and applies himself self-reflectively and against all conventions of classical narrative cinema. Jean Luc-Godard is a great admirer of both Russia and of Russian cinema, from Sergei Eisenstein to Dziga Vertov.</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>Concept, direction, performance: <strong>Andrei Andrianov, Oleg Soulimenko</strong><br />Dramaturgy: <strong>Judith Helmer</strong><br />Artistic advice: <strong>Robert Steijn</strong><br />Translation: <strong>Martin Jandl</strong><br />Stage set and costume: <strong>Anke Philipp</strong><br />Light design: <strong>Bartek Kubiak</strong><br />Video editing and photography: Elena Tikhonova<br />Video appearance: Dasha Andrianova and Alevtina Golubeva<br />Production management: Nicole Schuchardt<br />Co-produced by: Oleg Soulimenko/Vienna Magic; brut Wien; artblau-Tanzwerkstatt<br />Brunswick; Szene Salzburg<br />In collaboration with: Dance Agency TSEKH Moscow, Sophiensaele Berlin<br />Supported by the Cultural Department of the City of Vienna, the Federal Ministry for Education, Arts and Culture, the State of Lower Saxony, and Kultur Kontakt Austria<br />Duration: 70&acute;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>NB! Performance is in English and Russian without translation!</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>PRESS :</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\"The two performers chafe at Russian cultural clich&eacute;s as they are displayed in a Russian reading. With details, allusions and quotations-Soulimenko embodies Plisetskaya, Andrianov plays Godard-an ironic spectrum of inter-cultural ways of playing beyond the fussiness of semiofficial, representational-cultural understanding among nations opens up.\"<br />Helmut Ploebst, DER STANDARD, April 15, 2009</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\"The performance can hardly be topped in wit and ingenuity and masterly plays with clich&eacute;s and prejudices. A direct hit!\"<br />Helene Kurz, Wiener Zeitung, April 25, 2009</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>[popimg] oleg-oh-01.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] oleg-oh-02.jpg %%  Allkiri [/popimg]</p>',1,'','<p>Kanuti Gildi SAAL<br /><span class=\"suur\">OLEG SULIMENKO &amp; ANDREI ANDRIANOV</span> /VENEMAA-AUSTRIA/ <span class=\"keskmine\">\"Made in Russia\" </span></p>');
INSERT INTO `saal_events_en` VALUES (243,'','<p>Dobro do&scaron;li! / Welcome!</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>A year ago two young artists were chosen to present their country in a competitive European theatre world. They bravely answered this challenge, creating a masterpiece of modern theatre called \"Geography victims\". But their journey was plagued by misfortune, misunderstanding and other hardships. They were banned, they were censored. But now they&acute;re back! With a new concept. And there are three of them. Triple the size, triple the adventure. Their goal - to present their homeland in the best possible way - \"Geography victims 2 - the return of the victim\".<br />This is their story...</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>In 2011 Croatia is supposed to become a member of the EU. Miran Kurspahi&#263; and Rona ?ulj have had their project named \'Geography Victims\' as to refer, in this theatrical experience, especially on geographical, geopolitical, political, sociological, socio-political and even completely private aspects of being and living in a pre-European homeland of theirs. Such theme, oriented at the first sight narrowly inter-theatrically, becomes widened in its relevancy as the issues and thinking become more openly applicable, questioning the problems of micro politics and politics of art, private mechanisms of doing and reflection of these mechanisms in one\'s artistic actions, creation of private, author\'s and stage identities, presentation of an identity before the other and by the other, questions of belonging and a will to come out, to present.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Miran Kurspahi&#263;</strong>, an enfant terrible of the Croatian there scene is always willing to act without hesitation or any limitations. His pathological need to ironize every person and every event in his immediate and distant surroundings usually results in a determined self-irony. He loves cats as well as spirits. Especially Croatian schnapps called &Scaron;ljivovica. He constantly emphasizes that anger is the main impulse for his artistic, social and athletic activities.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Rona ?ulj</strong> gives 30% of herself 80% of the time. She has as aversion to direct confrontations and actions that are not necessary, but she is still always prepared to defend herself and, form a half autistic position, to launch criticism, which guarantees that lively discussion will not take place. At the same time she makes sure that her attitude, artistic as well as personal, is indisputable. She loves horses and pretentious words such as \"aloofness\". Her perfect complexion is a result of using olive oil from the Island of Hvar.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Sven Jakir</strong> is an academic actor. Sweet, honest, blonde, blonder than Sweden, Jakir often plays smart and emphasizes that playing smart is better than playing pretty which obviously refers to Kurspahi&#263;s lifestyle. Also, he is the biggest victim, bigger than the other five. Imagine (or look at the picture) how its like to be a Balcanian in heart and Sweden in appearance. Svens outside do not fit. Inappropriate balcanian wit is his only survival kit.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Dean Kriva&#269;i&#263;</strong> is very professional in what he is doing. As an actor he is a three time award winner. His best qualities are loyalty and Christianity. Although a gypsy in his heart, in 1992 he converted to Catholicism and since then is mostly seen in church. Besides the almighty he loves football and his gorgeous Argentinian catholic wife Renata. Every night before sleep he brunches with Dalmatian prosciutto, oven baked bread and a few or more glasses of domestic black wine.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Vanja Vascarac</strong> is a fully-fledged member of Generation X and a gentle cynic living in a world that swings between harsh naivety and cruel paranoia. He often feels like a pip in an olive, A professional film director, stuck in theatre, he partially enjouyes work of Kurspahi&#263; &amp; ?ulj as well as eating cheese from the Island of Pag in enormous amounts.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Petra Glad</strong> is an independent theatre producer dependant of the theatres who engage her. First of all she is a solid stander. Same as the White house in Washington, Petra Glad is made of famous building stone from Island Bra&#269;. She is constantly dieting but its hard whan you are a rock.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>Idea, Direction, Dramaturgy: <strong>Miran Kurspahi&#263;, Rona ?ulj </strong><br />Performers: <strong>Dean Kriva&#269;i&#263;, Sven Jakir, Miran Kurspahi&#263; </strong><br />Video: <strong>Vanja Vascarac </strong><br />Producer: <strong>Petra Glad</strong><br />Connections Mentor: <strong>Natasa Rajkovi&#263; </strong><br />Production: The Student Center, Universit&auml;t Zagreb<br />Coproduction: CONNECTIONS <br />*Performed in English with German, Italian and French subtitles</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>CONNECTIONS</strong> is an initiative of the theatre festival SPIELART  Munich in Cooperation with CAMPO - Gent, Republique - Copenhagen, Forum  Freies Theater - D&uuml;sseldorf, Theaterhaus Gessnerallee - Z&uuml;rich, Huis en  Festival a/d Werf - Utrecht, Choreographisches Zentrum NRW/PACT  Zollverein - Essen, Theater im Pumpenhaus - M&uuml;nster, Kanuti Gildi SAAL -  Tallinn, The Student Center - Zagreb.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>[img] eu-oh-200.jpg [/img]</p>\r\n<p>This project has been funded with support of the European Commission</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>[img] ksb_SW-150-oh.jpg [/img]</p>\r\n<p>Funded by the German <br />Federal Cultural Foundation</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Photos: Vanja Vascarac</p>\r\n<p>[popimg] horvaadid-oh-11.jpg %% Allkiri  [/popimg] [popimg] horvaadid-oh-12.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg]  horvaadid-oh-13.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg]</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Photos: Damir ?i?i&#263;</p>\r\n<p>[popimg] horvaadid-oh-01.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg]  horvaadid-oh-02.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] horvaadid-oh-03.jpg  %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] horvaadid-oh-04.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg]  [popimg] horvaadid-oh-05.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg]</p>\r\n<p>[popimg]  horvaadid-oh-06.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] horvaadid-oh-07.jpg %%  Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg] horvaadid-oh-08.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg]  [popimg] horvaadid-oh-09.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg] [popimg]  horvaadid-oh-10.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg]</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=C-p2XfcoSEA\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=C-p2XfcoSEA</a><br /><a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kkLvpvqaTZg&amp;feature=related\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kkLvpvqaTZg&amp;feature=related</a><br /><a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mIgshVnBWkc\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mIgshVnBWkc</a><br /><a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XsXvfbIrKGk&amp;feature=related\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XsXvfbIrKGk&amp;feature=related</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>PRESS:</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>In the manner of a cabaret show, through the performance we are witnessing a joyful satire dealing with different prejudices of the pre-european society. Dean Kriva&#269;i&#263;, Sven Jakir and Miran Kurspahi&#263; are on the stage talking about their work and questioning themselves about the best way to represent Croatia. In the well known Kurspahi&#263; method of activating the auditorium, the audience was given a role of international producers (all of us got a calling card of the actors), and provoked about their questionable sexuality and nationality (we all know that gays and jews rock the theatre world). The final scene emphasizes the form of a political cabaret; Dean Kriva&#269;i&#263; sings Danke Dautschland, dressed in both Croatian and German flag. There is a glove hanging from his behind. And guess what sign is on the glove. The yellow European stars.<br />Iva Grui&#263;, Jutarnji list</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Kurspahi&#263; &amp; ?ulj successfully developed a selfironizing, provocative but also very manipulative performance with lots of parody. Geography victims is a witty and delightful patchwork formed in mildly Monty Python style, a story about Croatia and her European future...<br />Helena Braut, Vjesnik</p>\r\n<p><br />Geography victims - a commercial. Though not for Croatia but for authors themselves... Whie actors on stage try to sell themselves to the audience, the main objectives comes to the surface; from the concrete ones like geographical position, well known tourist locations, gastronomic menu etc actors lead us all the way to fully understanding Balcanian mentality; true emotions are introduced and revealed through singing and dancing. Structurally, performance is consisted of numerous closed episodes dealing with theatrical and metatheatrical inquestioning of the theatre act itself. Actors test different methods of acting and actions on the stage; they use classic narration, story telling, mine and many more. The content of the episodes goes from strictly informational to some very playful and humorous demonstrations, like the one of Croatian folklore followed by great video presentation of literature used for making the scene. In this highly physical performance, actors are crossing the borders of the stage and mingle with the public offering them cheese and ham, Croatian &scaron;ljivovica and are in constant search for a producer. Behind all of the humour and wittiness, and the end, lies the truth about our preeuropean reality and a very well formed critique of political and social bearers of the country. I think I can predict a good box office result to Geography victims.<br />Igor Tretinjak</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>A junction of stand up comedy and pure ritual pleasure, a good form for presenting domestic mentality. Kurspahi&#263; and ?ulj are playing with the clich&eacute;, presenting the beautiness of Croatian shore and Balkan excitement while singing, shouting and shooting, they are opening important questions about Croatia as a part of the European Union. Kurspahi&#263; is, as always, slightly auto-ironic when in search for a better \"European\" producer. Well, judging by the number of his work that Theatre &amp;TD produced through past seasons, it seems that he has found one. Fortunately for the Croatian theatre scene which screams for diversity. Even if it was a bit narcistic and infantile.<br />Igor Ru?8i&#263;, Radio 101</p>',1,'','<p><span class=\"suur\">MIRAN KURSPAHIC &amp; RONA ZULJ</span> /Croatia/</p>\r\n<p class=\"keskmine\"><span class=\"keskmine\">\"Geography victims 2: return of the victim\"</span></p>');
