;ev 12.08.11</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://etv.err.ee/arhiiv.php?id=119778\" target=\"_blank\">2011</a>&nbsp;- ETV, 31.07.2011 (starting from 02:06 up to 07.01)</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',1,'','<p><strong>August DanceFestival 2011</strong></p>\r\n<div>\r\n<p>15-31.08 Tallinn</p>\r\n</div>');
INSERT INTO `saal_events_en` VALUES (358,'','<p>\"This is not a love story\" is a story of two reluctant heroes - Kowalski and Vera.&nbsp;At least that\'s their names in one of the scenes. They talk, dance and never stop&nbsp;asking questions: Who did what? When? Where? And why?</p>\r\n<p>A delicate search for context and connections, which always seem to be slightly&nbsp;beyond our reach, the journey becomes not about the destination, but the&nbsp;transformation and reflection along the way. The journey keeps starting over. Again&nbsp;and again as in a road movie dance.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>From the script:</p>\r\n<p>K: - Here I was supposed to come in with 10 dogs, frozen to death. But there was</p>\r\n<p>absolutely no way we could bring them.</p>\r\n<p>J: - I start here.</p>\r\n<p>K: - I stop here.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\"This is not a love story\" was created in residenci\r\n<script src=\"http://www.saal.ee/ohjur/tiny_mce/themes/advanced/langs/en.js\" type=\"text/javascript\"></script>\r\nes at Arts Academy in Tromso,&nbsp;Alkantara, Lisboa, Dancecity, Newcastle, SIN Culture Centre, Budapest, Saxn&auml;s,&nbsp;Sweden, Steirischer Herbst, Graz, Austria, SITE, Stockholm and premiered at&nbsp;Dansens Hus, Stockholm May 2011.</p>\r\n<p>Gunilla Heilborn is one of Sweden\'s most popular choreographers. With an existential&nbsp;flair, Heilborn has brought both laughter and reflection to audiences with such works&nbsp;as \"The Five Year Plan\", \"Potato Country\" and \"This is Alaska\".&nbsp;Both Johan Thelander and Kristiina Viiala are frequent collaborators with Heilborn.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Gunilla Heilborn is a choreographer and film maker based in Stockholm, producing&nbsp;and touring nationally and internationally. Her productions are supported by the&nbsp;Swedish Arts Council, the Culture Committee of Stockholm and the Swedish Arts&nbsp;Grants Committee.</p>\r\n<p>After studies at the Tamalpa Institute in San Francisco, USA and the program of&nbsp;choreography at the University of Dance in Stockholm 95-98 she has created&nbsp;performances and movies with great success for both adult and children audience.&nbsp;Heilborns\' unique way of combining text, motion, video and images, always spiced&nbsp;with humor and a cool irony, has given her an indisputable position as one of&nbsp;Sweden\'s most interesting performance and film artists.</p>\r\n<p>Gunilla Heilborns\' last creation for her own ensemble \"The Five Year Plan\" opened to&nbsp;rave reviews at NorrlandsOperan in Ume&aring;, Sweden Nov 1st 2009 and was&nbsp;performed in Stockholm at the venue C/O at Stockholm City Theatre.</p>\r\n<p>Her piece \"Potato Country\" premiered at Dansens Hus in Stockholm, Sweden in&nbsp;2007. The piece was restaged for two performance periods in Stockholm, first at&nbsp;Kulturhuset in March 2009 and later on at the Park Theatre in August 2009 (for more&nbsp;than 3,000 spectators). The piece has been invited and performed in venues in&nbsp;Belarus, Finland, Germany and the United States. In the spring of 2009 collaborated&nbsp;with the G&ouml;teborg Ballet for the first time, creating the critically acclaimed \"Alaska\".</p>\r\n<p>Her films include \"The Lodge\" (nominated for Best Screen Choreography at Dance&nbsp;Screen Brighton 2005 and nominated for the Swedish Guldbagge Award for best&nbsp;short film in Sweden 2005) and \"Rewind\" (nominated for best short film at the&nbsp;Guldbagge Awards in Sweden, 2003). Her latest film, \"What you do\", created&nbsp;together with M&aring;rten Nilsson and Kim Hiorth&oslash;y, was awarded the Guldbagge Award&nbsp;for best short film in 2007.</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>Staging: Gunilla Heilborn</p>\r\n<p>Choreography and text: Gunilla Heilborn, Johan Thelander, Kristiina Viiala</p>\r\n<p>Dancers: Johan Thelander, Kristiina Viiala</p>\r\n<p>Set and costume design: Katarina Wiklund</p>\r\n<p>Light design: Miriam Helleday</p>\r\n<p>Music: Kim Hiorth&oslash;y</p>\r\n<p>Sound design: Johan Adling</p>\r\n<p>Photo: Kim Hiorthoy</p>\r\n<p>Photos of the performance: Stefan Bohlin</p>\r\n<p>Technical supervision: Lumination</p>\r\n<p>Production management, financing: Magnus Nordberg/Nordberg Movement</p>\r\n<p>Tour manager: Emmy Astbury</p>\r\n<p>Managing director: &Aring;sa Edgren/Loco Motion</p>\r\n<p>Production, management: LOCO MOTION</p>\r\n<p>This is not a love story is a coproduction between Gunilla Heilborn, NorrlandsOperan,</p>\r\n<p>G&ouml;teborgs Dans- och Teaterfestival with the support of EU\'s culture program through</p>\r\n<p>NXT STP and Dansens Hus. Gunilla Heilborn is supported by the Swedish Arts</p>\r\n<p>Council, the Culture Committee of Stockholm and the Swedish Arts Grants</p>\r\n<p>Committee.</p>\r\n<p>Performance in Tallinn is presented in co-operation with Festival Baltoscandal and supported by NXTSTP, with the support of Culture Program of the European Union.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.gunillaheilborn.se\">www.gunillaheilborn.se</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>[popimg] gunilla-01-oh.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg]&nbsp;[popimg] gunilla-02-oh.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg]&nbsp;[popimg] gunilla-03-oh.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg]&nbsp;[popimg] gunilla-04-oh.jpg %% Allkiri [/popimg]</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>PRESS:</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.sirp.ee/index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=12824:harjumuspaeratult-tantsurohke-tantsulavastus-&amp;catid=3:teater&amp;Itemid=2&amp;issue=3354\" target=\"_blank\">Harjumusp&auml;ratult tantsurohke tantsulavastus</a>&nbsp;- Evelyn Raudsepp, Sirp 12.08.11</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p><em>&#1040;&#1042;&#1043;&#1059;&#1057;&#1058;&#1054;&#1042;&#1057;&#1050;&#1048;&#1049; &#1060;&#1045;&#1057;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1040;&#1051;&#1068; &#1058;&#1040;&#1053;&#1062;&#1040; 2011</em></p>\r\n<p><em>15.08 / 20:00 / Kanuti Gildi SAAL</em></p>\r\n<p><strong><em>&#1043;&#1059;&#1053;&#1048;&#1051;&#1051;&#1040; &#1061;&#1045;&#1049;&#1051;&#1041;&#1054;&#1056;&#1053;</em></strong><em>&nbsp;/&#1057;&#1090;&#108